<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Says It May Have Killed Convoy Civilians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) formally acknowledged Monday that it may have
killed civilians in attacks last Wednesday on two convoys
traveling between Prizren and Djakovica in Kosovo, but declined
to give the number.
</P>
<P>
A NATO air force commander, Brig. Gen. Dan Leaf, told reporters
at NATO headquarters that there is the possibility that
civilian-type vehicles were struck and "there may have been
civilian personnel harmed." But he said NATO "can't determine that
clearly."
</P>
<P>
However, a NATO civilian spokesman, Jamie Shea, confirmed here
at a daily news briefing last Thursday that a NATO aircraft caused
civilian damage after bombing a convoy in Kosovo. "The NATO bomb
destroyed the lead vehicle which we now believe to have been a
civilian vehicle," he said while acknowledging an incident at a
site near Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
But journalists here challenged NATO spokesmen about the
bombing sites and casualty figures during mid-afternoon daily news
briefings these days.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav authorities reported about 80 people died from the
April 14 attacks in Kosovo, while Western journalists were also
trying to identify the exact details about the civilian tragedy.
</P>
<P>
One of the attacks was the subject of graphic Serb television
film showing blown-up tractors and the bodies of ethnic Albanians
on a road in Kosovo. Gen. Leaf said that reporters taken by
Yugoslav officials to the scene saw about 20 casualties. "I cannot
explain the bodies shown on Serb TV," the U.S. commander from
NATO's Aviano base in Italy said.
</P>
<P>
During about the one-hour briefing, Leaf gave reporters a
detailed account of NATO attacks on two convoys near Djakovica
over a two-hour period on April 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
