<HEADLINE> General Motors, Toyota To Jointly Develop Fuel-Cell Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 19 (Xinhua) -- General Motors Corp. and
Toyota Motor Corp. said Monday they have reached a five-year
agreement to jointly develop cars powered by fuel cells and other
non-traditional fuel technologies.
</P>
<P>
A report from General Motors Corp. said the new venture will
involve research and development of electric, hybrid electric and
fuel-cell technology.
</P>
<P>
Experts say fuel cells produce electricity using a chemical
reaction between hydrogen and oxygen and produce little or no
emissions, and the technology was developed for use in spacecraft,
but problems in supplying and storing hydrogen have hampered plans
to use it for cars.
</P>
<P>
The hybrid electric vehicles, they said, typically combine an
electric motor with other power systems. So far, fuel cells remain
prohibitively expensive, they added.
</P>
<P>
"Pooling our efforts should result in commercially viable and
advanced technologies faster and at a lower cost to our customers,
and as breakthroughs are reached, suppliers will be able to count
on the volume of production from two of the world's largest
automakers," GM Vice Chairman Harry Pearce said in a Detroit news
conference.
</P>
<P>
GM, the world's largest automaker, was the first to mass-market
an electric car, the EV1, which has failed to catch on in the
markets where it is being leased. Toyota, the world's third
largest, brought the first hybrid electric car to market, the
Prius, in Japan two years ago.
</P>
<P>
GM and Toyota have worked together on projects before, the most
recent of which was an agreement in June 1998 to develop and
improve the electric vehicle inductive charging system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
