<HEADLINE> Kuwait Reiterates Bigger Role of Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 19 (Xinhua) -- A senior Kuwaiti official
reiterated Monday the need to expand the role of the private
sector in the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Promoting privatization is necessary to increase non-oil
revenues, create jobs for nationals, enhance efficiency of
national manpower and widen participation in obtaining new
technology, Oil Minister Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah said during
the foundation laying ceremony of the Kuwait Catalyst Company.
</P>
<P>
He said the Kuwaiti government has exerted much of its efforts
over the past few years in planning for a most effective future
economic path and taking into consideration the importance of
activating the role of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
"The new century we are approaching is bringing along with it
numerous opportunities, the opening of countries and the
integration of their economies into one market, in which the
private sector is playing a very important role while the
government is increasingly shifting its role to supervisory and
regulatory function," Saud added.
</P>
<P>
In face of the sagging oil prices which heavily reduced its
state revenues, Kuwait has been attaching great importance to
boosting the role of the private sector, which at present
involves mainly in the service industry.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti government is also considering to privatize some
of its properties, including affiliates of the state-owned
petroleum corporation.
</P>
<P>
Related government ministries have implemented a number of
measures designed to encourage more investment in private
sector.
</P>
<P>
Since the private sector, in which cheap foreign labor
accounts for more than 98 percent of the 600,000 employees, has
been reluctant to accept local workers, the government is urged to
introduce an effective mechanism for imposing decisions and
legislation of limiting the employment of skilled expatriates.
</P>
</TEXT>
