<HEADLINE> N. Ireland Peace Talks to Resume Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
said here Monday the talks on Northern Ireland's peace process
were to resume early next week.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after leading politicians from the province met in
Downing Street, Ahern said there had been no breakthrough in
attempts to end the deadlock over arms.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Ahern met representatives
from the three main parties separately for five hours in total.
</P>
<P>
"It is extremely difficult, there is no hiding that fact. I
don't expect either side to lose all. Neither do I expect them to
ask each other to win all. I think they have to lose to get a
solution," Ahern told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Ahern said that despite the apparent lack of progress, the
dialogue would continue and not be "parked."
</P>
<P>
"The only thing that was agreed is that no one wants to park
the agreement. That means we have to keep up an intensive round of
(talks) trying to find a way through or around the obvious
impasse," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also urged both Sinn Fein and Unionists to give ground on
the decommissioning which has blocked the peace process for
several months.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Blair said that all the parties agreed there
was no question of sidelining the process. "There is a shared
determination to crack this," he said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Unionists insist the IRA hand over its arms before its
political wing Sinn Fein to join the local government.
</P>
<P>
But the IRA has made clear it will not hand over -- or
decommission -- its weapons as the precondition was not stipulated
in the peace agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
