<HEADLINE> Security Council Welcomes Annan's Efforts on Kosovo Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The president of the U.N.
Security Council, Alain Dejammet of France, Monday said that the
15-member Council welcomes the efforts by U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on the solution of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Council also agreed that the world body should "play a
significant role" on Kosovo, a Serbian province, Dejammet said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press here, Dejammet said, "Members
of the Security Council confirmed that they welcomed the efforts
of the Secretary-General to the solution of the crisis."
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General expressed his conviction that the U.N.
should play a significant role. He called upon the members of the
Security Council to rebuild their unity on this issue. He declared
himself determined to continue his efforts and he confirmed his
intentions to appoint diplomatic envoys to the region," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Council members "agree with the conviction expressed by the
Secretary-General of the necessity for the U.N. to play a
significant role," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Security Council approved the intention of the
Secretary-General to appoint diplomatic envoys and they approved
his intentions to go himself soon to Germany and to Moscow," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after a closed-door Security Council meeting
on Kosovo, at which Annan briefed the Council members on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
During the briefing, Annan told the Security Council, "I
believe that there is broad consensus that the United Nations
should play a significant role in the search for a diplomatic
solution aimed at ensuring lasting peace and stability in the
region."
</P>
<P>
Martin Griffiths, deputy to the Under-Secretary-General for
Humanitarian Affairs, also briefed the Security Council on the
humanitarian situation in and around Kosovo, a southern province
in the Yugoslav Republic of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the U.N. spokesman issued a statement, announcing that
Annan will pay a visit to Germany on April 26-28 and Russia on
April 29 to seek a diplomatic solution on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said last Friday that the
U.N. chief believes that "we are involved in a difficult,
dangerous and intractable situation," and "we are only at the
beginning stage of our search for a diplomatic solution."
</P>
<P>
Over the past few days, Annan, who just returned from his
Europe tour, made wide contacts either by face-to-face meetings
with representatives of the five permanent members of the Security
Council or telephone talks with leaders of several countries,
diplomatic sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
