<HEADLINE> Security Council Urges Taleban to Resume Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council Monday urged the Afghan warring party the Taleban
to return to the negotiating table shortly.
</P>
<P>
The move came as the Security Council was briefed by Lakhsar
Brahimi, U.N. Special Envoy on Afghanistan, on the latest
developments in the country.
</P>
<P>
Expressing its concern at the military preparations carried out
by warring parties of the country, the Council reiterated that
there was no alternative to a peace settlement, on the basis of
the relevant resolutions of the Security Council and the General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The Council called on the parties to cooperate with the U.N. to
establish mechanisms to prevent the escalation of the fighting and
to undertake confidence-building measures.
</P>
<P>
The Council reiterated their demand that the Taleban fully
comply with their obligations to ensure the security of
international personnel returning to the country, which remained
an immutable prerequisite for resumption of U.N. full-fledged
activities in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Council expressed firm support for the efforts of the "Six
Plus Two" Group to facilitate the peace process in Afghanistan and
called upon them to continue preparation for the meeting of the
members of the Group in Tashkent, and to exert their influence
over the parties in the most effective manner.
</P>
<P>
The Taleban decided last week to cancel the talks to be held in
mid-April in Afghanistan, which is the continuation of the resumed
talks between the Taleban and the the northern-based alliance in
Ashgabat, Turkmenistan in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
