<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Returns Home From Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
returned home Monday after a two-day official visit to Libya where
he, together with other regional leaders, signed a communique
calling for an immediate cease-fire in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Museveni was met by Vice President Specioza Kazibwe and Prime
Minister Apolo Nsibambi at the Entebbe International Airport
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The communique signed by Museveni, DRC President Laurent Kabila
and other regional leaders called for an immediate cease-fire in
the third largest African country to pave way for a peaceful
settlement to the eight- month conflict.
</P>
<P>
Rebels in the DRC, however, have given a cautious response to
the reported cease-fire agreement, Radio Uganda reported Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Rebel leader Wamba dia Wamba said that he has not yet seen the
contents of the agreement, but he assumed that the rebel allies
will not act against their interests.
</P>
<P>
On the agreement, European Union Envoy to the Great Lakes
region, Aldo Ajello, was quoted as saying that the agreement is a
good sign in finding a peaceful solution to the DRC crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
