<HEADLINE> Israel's Fallen Soldiers of Wars Remembered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Sirens sounded around Israel
Monday night to mark the beginning of the Memorial Day for the
country's soldiers fallen in wars.
</P>
<P>
President Ezer Weizman called for soul-searching and national
reconciliation when speaking at a ceremony held near the Western
Wall, the holiest place for the Jews, in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
A two-minute siren will also sound Tuesday morning and will be
followed by state ceremonies at 42 military cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
The names of the 18,939 Israeli soldiers fallen in various
wars since November 1947, when the United Nations Partition Plan
for Palestine was adopted, were screened on Israel's televisions.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army imposed a full closure on the West Bank and
Gaza Strip for the Memorial day and the following Independence
Day, which ends Wednesday at sunset.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers manning roadblocks have been ordered to allow passage
in "humanitarian and urgent medical cases," the army said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
