<HEADLINE> U.S. Stocks Tumble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks tumbled
Monday with the Dow Jones industrial average soaring as high as
270 points in the morning but retreating in the afternoon. The
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index dived severely.
</P>
<P>
At 2:50 p.m. EST, the Dow was up 19.38 at 10,474.51 while the
Nasdaq was down 103.38 at 2,380.66.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Dow posted its fifth consecutive closing at
10,493.89 Friday due to investors' swing from technology stocks
into industrial stocks.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index closed the week at 2,484.04 from
Monday's record 2,598.81. The index jumped 39.6 percent in 1998
and saw continued upswing in January. After a setback in February
and March, it took a rapid recovery in the first week of April.
</P>
<P>
Investors' confidence in technology stocks was partly erased by
computer giant Compaq's recent announcement on its dismal earnings
projections as a result of low personal computer prices.
</P>
<P>
Among the Dow gainers were financial stocks Monday. The biggest
U.S. financial services company, Citigroup, reported a 12 percent
rise in its profits to 2.42 billion U.S. dollars in the first
quarter of 1999 from a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
