<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Urges Concerted Efforts Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
Monday urged scientists not to exclude anybody who may have any
intelligence about the HIV/AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to them to work together to overcome the problem in
a speech read for him by Minister of Presidency Ruhakana Rugunda
at the Uganda Virus Research Institute (UVRI) in Entebbe, 40
kilometers south of capital Kampala.
</P>
<P>
At the occasion marking 10 years of HIV/AIDS research
cooperation between the British Medical Research Council and the
Ugandan institute, Museveni hailed the joint venture output which
made Uganda one of the four privileged countries from the
developing world to have access to the anti- AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
The president in his written speech also called upon the
researchers at the institute to maintain a high profile research
so that AIDS may be further tamed and eventually eliminated.
</P>
<P>
Museveni attributed Uganda's success story in its fight against
the epidemic to the ruling National Resistance Movement's openness
which dramatically increased people's awareness of the dangers of
the disease.
</P>
<P>
With collective efforts by various groups and organizations,
incidence of HIV/AIDS in Uganda has dropped from over 30 percent
10 years ago to the present level of less than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has been regarded as one of the success stories in
checking the spread of the pandemic in the whole world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
