<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Offer Facilities to High-Tech Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will provide attractive
facilities for investors from China, Japan and South Korea in
projects built in a technology valley, Ismailia governor said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Aziz Salama told the Middle East News Agency that
Ismailia governorate is to offer facilities to the industrial
projects concluded during President Hosni Mubarak's recent visit
to the three Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak traveled to China, South Korea and Japan on April
5-13. During the visit, Egypt reached scores of agreements on
economic cooperation and establishment of joint ventures with the
three countries.
</P>
<P>
Salama said the planned technology valley will be developed on
an area of 6,720 hectares near the east bank of the Suez Canal.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises set up in the valley are required to produce
electronics, semi-conductors, wireless equipment and computer
software, he said, adding that 85 percent of the products are
export-oriented.
</P>
<P>
He expected high returns from the projects due to the valley's
advantageous geographical position, which is close to the
international waterway and the European and African markets.
</P>
<P>
Products of the valley will also enjoy facilities and
preferential advantages in the Arab and African markets under
agreements Egypt signed with Arab and African countries.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has sealed with other Arab countries agreements on
economic and trade cooperation, including those on free trade
zones. The country became a member of the Common Market of Eastern
and Southern Africa in June 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
