<HEADLINE> Lebanon Urges U.N. to Force Israel to Withdraw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon Monday urged the
United Nations Security Council to force Israel to quit a village
it included last week in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Security Council, Lebanese U.N.
representative Samir Moubarak said Israel sent 50 men into the
village of Arnoun on April 15 in company with a tank, an armored
personnel carrier and a jeep.
</P>
<P>
"In a new attempt to include it into the occupied zone in the
south, they separated Arnoun from the liberated area and proceeded
to arrest residents and to prevent inhabitants from entering," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"In bringing this dangerous development to the attention of the
Secretary-General, the members of the Security Council and the
international community, the Lebanese government urged swift
action to put an end to a situation that constitutes a flagrant
violation of the Charter of the United Nations and the principles
of international law," Moubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Moubarak also urged implementation of a 1978 Security Council
resolution that called on Israel to withdraw from southern
Lebanon. 
