<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief to Visit Germany, Russia on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan is scheduled to pay a visit to Germany and Russia on
Kosovo, a Serbian province, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Eckhard said, "the
Secretary-General will be making a long-planned official visit to
Germany from 26 to 28 April."
</P>
<P>
"After consulting with the Russian Government, he has extended
this trip by one day to visit Moscow on 29 April," the statement
added.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after Annan Monday morning briefed a
closed-door Security Council session on Kosovo. He is expected to
appoint a special envoy on Kosovo, diplomatic sources here said,
but the name of the would-be envoy remains unknown at the moment.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General was not invited to attend the NATO
anniversary celebration in Washington," Eckhard said, referring to
the Washington summit marking the 50th anniversary of NATO on
April 23-25 in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council convened the closed-door session on Kosovo
after several countries recently proposed solutions on how to
solve the question of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who said earlier "not directly involved in the Kosovo
crisis," is began a new round of diplomacy on Kosovo. The U.N.
chief, describing the current situation in Kosovo following the
ongoing NATO bombing as "difficult and dangerous," said last week
that one cannot expect "quick result," and "we are in the
beginning of the diplomatic meditation."
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Qin Huasun, Chinese permanent representative to
the United Nations, told reporters after the Council meeting that
"we are in favor of a political solution of the question of
Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
"We believe that any political solution should be based on two
principles, namely faithful respect for and maintenance of the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of the FRY (Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia), and protection of the legitimate rights of all
ethnic groups in Kosovo, the FRY," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, it is very important to seek the consent of
the Government of the FRY when any plan is to be discussed," Qin
said. "We are against imposing any solution on the FRY. As for
now, it is a matter of priority for NATO to cease immediately its
military action against the FRY."
</P>
<P>
NATO, without the authorization of the Security Council,
unilaterally launched air strikes on Yugoslavia, a sovereign and
independent member of the U.N. family, violating the U.N. Charter
and international law.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing air attacks also created a large exodus of refugees
and a serious humanitarian crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
