<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parliament Returns to Historic Reichstag Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 19 (xinhua) -- Nearly nine years after the
reunification of West and East Germany, the German parliament, the
Bundestag, Monday officially returned from Bonn to the historic
Reichstag building in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
On the flower-decorated steps of the building, German President
Roman Herzog, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder with his entire
cabinet, and ex-Chancellor Helmut Kohl attended the handover
ceremony, at which parliamentary spokesman Wolfgang Thierse
received keys to the Reichstag from the British architect Sir
Norman Foster.
</P>
<P>
Foster directed the reconstruction of the building 66 years
after it had been burnt by the Nazis and 54 years after it had
been destroyed in World War II.
</P>
<P>
The Reichstag, as the structure will continue to be called, was
designed by architect Paul Wallot, and was in 1894 inaugurated by
the then German Emperor Wilhelm II.
</P>
<P>
It had been the seat of the German parliament until 1933, when
the Nazis under Adolf Hitler seized the power. The parliament
played no role in the Nazi era.
</P>
<P>
Sixty years after Germany launched the second world war,
Monday's ceremony was featured with a statement by Schroeder, who
said Germany, by participating in the NATO air strikes against
Yugoslavia, had begun taking responsibility for other nations with
alteration in generations of its leadership.
</P>
<P>
"To me, here is the right site and right time to draw the
interim balance of the united Germany," Schroeder said. "(It's)
the right site because that Berlin symbolizes the united
Germany,... the right time because the united Germany has
fulfilled its political alteration in generations."
</P>
<P>
There is no other country in the world than Germany, which has
not changed its policy significantly after the the generation who
experienced World War II withdrawing from the political stage,
Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
"The right time is also because, as the events has dramatically
run in the past weeks and months, Germany has changed its role in
the world. After years of being separated and standing behind the
affairs, we are now deferently and more intensively taking
responsibility for the fate of people in other countries," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In its first direct campaign operation after World War II,
Germany has been taking part in the NATO air raids against
Yugoslavia from the very beginning in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deutsche Telekom, Telecom Italia Reached Merger Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- One of the world's largest
telecommunications groups valued at some 200 billion U.S. dollars
will be created after the German giant Deutsche Telekom merges
with Telecom Italia as they have agreed.
</P>
<P>
The two companies will announce details of the agreement at a
press conference in London Tuesday, the DPA news agency reported
Monday. Deutsche Telekom neither confirmed nor denied the
information.
</P>
<P>
The development follows days of intense speculation and reports
about their imminent merger to create a concern with a yearly
turnover of around 64 billion dollars and a work force of about
350,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
Deutsche Telekom just a week ago dismissed a Financial Times
report about the merger as "speculation," saying it would not
participate in such speculation.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, however, the German company while reporting
its first-quarter results also announced plans for a second
emission of shares which could generate as much as 12 billion
dollars in revenues.
</P>
<P>
The company said the share issue, to be effected by the summer,
would be used to bolster its finances and to help in making
acquisitions, a point which only further fueled the speculation
about its aims towards Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, German Finance Minister Hans Eichel and his
Italian counterpart, Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, respectively gave their
blessing to the merger at an informal European Union finance
ministers meeting, and said they would not stand against it.
</P>
<P>
The two companies Sunday formally confirmed their talks, which
had been believed to involve the two sides' top executives, Ron
Sommer of Deutsche Telekom and Franco Bernabe of Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
The German business daily Handelsblatt reported earlier Monday
that the two companies were intending a merger after the model of
the mega-fusion last year between Daimler and Chrysler, whereby
the shares of both would be exchanged in lieu of a single new
share.
</P>
<P>
Amid the developments, France Telecom, one of Deutsche
Telekom's most important international partners, warned Monday
against the merger with Telecom Italia, saying it viewed such a
merger as incompatible with Deutsche Telekom's efforts towards a
"strategic turnaround."
</P>
<P>
The French and German companies are involved together with the
U.S. telephone company Sprint in a joint venture called Global
One, which has reportedly run into problems with
larger-than-anticipated losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
