<HEADLINE> Egypt, Netherlands Hold Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Trade ministers of Egypt and the
Netherlands on Monday discussed here ways of promoting bilateral
ties in trade, economic cooperation and investment.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting, Egyptian Minister of
Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili said the two sides dealt with means
of boosting Dutch participation in Egypt's national projects.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is carrying out a number of giant projects in Sinai and
the southern valley to channel Nile water to reclaim land from
desert. The country is seeking foreign cooperation in developing
an industrial park in the northwest of the Gulf of Suez.
</P>
<P>
Gowaili said that he explored with Anneck Van Dok, who arrived
in Cairo on Sunday, Netherlands' technological assistance to
Egypt's small and medium industries in a bid to raise their
production and export capability.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's small and medium enterprises, which account for 99.7
percent of the non-agricultural private businesses, provide 80
percent of the value produced annually by the private sector and
employ 75 percent of the country's non-agricultural labor force.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian minister said the two sides also tackled means of
shoring up Dutch investments in Egypt, which he said stand at 1.3
billion Egyptian pounds (over 380 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Several agreements will be signed between the two countries on
enhancing trade and preventing dual taxation, said Afifi Selim,
official of Egypt's Ministry of Trade and Supply.
</P>
<P>
A memo of understanding is to be sealed between the two sides,
under which the Netherlands will grant Egypt 5 million dollars for
conducting feasibility studies on infrastructure projects, Selim
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
