<HEADLINE> Vojvodina PM: NATO Attacks European Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NOVI SAD, Yugoslavia, April 19 (Xinhua) -- A ranking official
of the northern Yugoslav province of Vojvodina said Monday that
the NATO attack on a government building here represents an attack
on European culture.
</P>
<P>
The building, of the provincial executive council, was hit by a
NATO missile at 01:34 a.m. local time. The interior of the
building was badly damaged but nobody was injured.
</P>
<P>
Council President Bosko Perosevic said the building was daily
frequented by members of all the 26 ethnic groups living in the
province and its only function was to provide administrative
services.
</P>
<P>
Fragments of the missile could be seen lying on the corridor of
the fifth floor. One fragment bears the letters and Arabic
numerals of EB02138.
</P>
<P>
Below the window where the missile hit, a radiator made of cast
iron was broken into bits and pieces, shattering windows and
locked doors nearby.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said they heard five detonations and planes roaring
overhead.
</P>
<P>
"The building is one of the most prominent symbols of Novi Sad,
and a shot taken at this building is a shot into the very heart of
European culture, because of the place it has in European
architecture," Perosevic said.
</P>
<P>
"This should be a signal to Europeans to oppose the insane
bombardments of our country," he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Perosevic inaugurated a new waterworks
network which normalized the supply of about 40,000 inhabitants of
Novi Sad districts on the western bank of the Danube -- Sremska
Kamenica, Petrovaradin, Sremski Karlovci, and other places which
have been without drinking water since NATO destroyed the Varadin
Bridge and the Freedom Bridge which also served to connect water
pipelines.
</P>
<P>
"The entire job which requires three months under normal
circumstances has been completed in just 10 days, and this is a
good example how one should tackle any difficulty caused by the
brutal NATO aggression," Perosevic said.
</P>
<P>
On the northern side of destroyed the Varadin Bridge, a barge
operated by the army was providing free transport for the
residents to cross the Danube river.
</P>
<P>
Gordan, 16, said he had to spend about one hour more to travel
between the two parts of the city following the destruction of the
bridge.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he was worrying about his father, who is in the army
guarding another bridge in Beska, a city some 30 kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
According to Perosevic, seven of the province's bridges were
bombed by NATO and four were totally destroyed, blocking
navigation along the Danube river.
</P>
<P>
And Novi Sad, the provincial capital some 80 kilometers north
of Belgrade, has been under NATO attacks almost daily since March
24 except three nights, Perosevic said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
