<HEADLINE> Angolan War Hinders Anti-Trypanosomiasis Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- War has seriously hindered the
Angolan government's efforts to wipe out trypanosomiasis, Deputy
Minister of Health Jose van Dunen said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Van Dunen said this at the re-opening ceremony of the
Trypanosomiasis Treatment Center in Viana City, 16 kilometers east
of capital Luanda.
</P>
<P>
The center, which can accommodate 42 patients, was reopened
with the help of the French government.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister noted that Angola is one of the countries
seriously affected by the disease, saying that nearly 30,000
people had reportedly infected with trypanosomiasis between 1975
and 1998.
</P>
<P>
But he added that the actual number must be much bigger than
this.
</P>
<P>
According to surveys conducted by some international health
organizations, half of the 10 million Angolans are threatened by
the disease.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan official pointed out that because of the civil war,
two research and treatment institutions in northern Uige Province,
one of the most seriously affected areas, had been forced to shut
down.
</P>
<P>
However, van Dunen pledged that his government will continue to
invest in the anti-trypanosomiasis drive, despite the renewed
civil war.
</P>
<P>
He also called upon donor countries and private institutions to
provide Angola with assistance so as to strengthen the efforts
made by the Angolan government.
</P>
<P>
At the same function, French Ambassador to Angola Andre Cida
said that his government will provide 1.12 million U.S. dollars in
addition to the funds for re-opening the Viana center.
</P>
<P>
Trypanosomiasis is a special kind of tropical disease in
Africa. It can kill people. The disease is infected through
bites by tsetse flies. The symptom of the disease is that the
patients always feel sleepy.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic is prevalent in northern provinces of Zaire, Uige
and Kwanza-Norte and central Benguela Province in the southern
African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0029 </DOCNO>
