<HEADLINE> Explosion in Nepal Govt Paper Remains Unanswered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Police are still investigating
into the bomb explosion which happened early Monday morning at the
office building of the government-owned Gorkhapatra daily but hurt
no body.
</P>
<P>
The explosion, which happened at two o'clock, damaged three
rooms of the paper's editorial section and left a hole at the end
of the bath room where the bomb was planted, Gyan Bahadur Rai
said. He is the acting editor-in-chief of The Rising Nepal, the
sister paper of the vernacular Gorkhapatra.
</P>
<P>
He said his English-language paper, which is also in the
building, was not affected.
</P>
<P>
The blast shattered window glasses of a nearby bank, he said,
adding that the property damaged was initially valued at 200,000
rupees (2,941 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Police suspect that the 10-kilogram bomb, possibly a time bomb,
could be planted by anti-social elements, Rai said.
</P>
<P>
Following the explosion, the worst in 20 years, the newspaper
is tightening security, he said.
</P>
<P>
Election to the House of Representatives is scheduled for May 3
and May 17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
