<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Seek Urgent Action on Oceans, Overfishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- At least 60 percent of
world fisheries are either fully exploited or overfished, 58
percent of the world's coral reefs are threatened by human
activity, and more than half of the world's coastal areas are at
high or moderate risk of environmental degradation, a new U.N.
report said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Commission on Sustainable Development, expected to
meet here on April 19-30, will focus this year on urgent action
needed to combat these problems. Environment ministers and other
top government officials will add their input at a high-level
segment on April 21-23.
</P>
<P>
The Commission, which follows up on the work of the 1992 Rio
Earth Summit, will build on debate generated by the 1998
International Year of the Ocean.
</P>
<P>
"This session is a real opportunity to take stock of the state
of the oceans," said Simon Upton, environment minister of New
Zealand and current chairman of the U.N. commission. "I am
committed to ensuring that governments focus on actions, not
words, in addressing these crucial issues." 
</P>
