<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Equity Prices Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Greece's equity prices fell
sharply Monday due to the fears of a prolonged war in Kosovo and
its impact on the Greek economy.
</P>
<P>
The Athens Stock Exchange's general index fell 4.87 percent to
3,386.09 points while the FTSE/ASE 20 index dropped 5.29 percent
to 2,115.85 points.
</P>
<P>
Broadly, decliners led advancers by 241 to 45 with another 7
issues unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Banks led the market decline with a 5.56 percent, with
industrials and miscellaneous losing 3.39 percent and 5.52 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Traders attributed the decline to the failure in diplomatic
initiatives to end the Kosovo war and fears of an escalation of
the war with NATO's possible deployment of ground troops in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Economists warned that the Kosovo crisis could reduce Greece's
gross domestic growth from a budget target of 3.5 percent this
year to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
They also estimated that the Kosovo crisis could cost the Greek
economy about 300 billion drachmas (about 1 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
