<HEADLINE> Bulgarian MPs to Vote on Granting NATO Access to Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The National Assembly of Bulgaria,
or parliament, will convene parliamentary members to vote on
whether to provide NATO access to Bulgarian airspace, President
Peter Stoyanov announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov made the announcement after consultations with
National Assembly Chairman Yordan Sokolov and Prime Minister Ivan
Kostov, following NATO's request on Saturday for access to
Bulgarian airspace to conduct operations in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The vote decision was approved by Stoyanov, Sokolov and Kostov.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after the consultations, Stoyanov said
Bulgaria's support for NATO actions is not intended to gain NATO
membership but is a way to choose peace.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria has already received security guarantees from NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana and will receive more security
guarantees during Kostov's visit to Brussels on Wednesday, the
president said.
</P>
<P>
The new guarantees will probably be in the form of a Bulgaria-
NATO agreement on complementing the Partnership for Peace
Agreement and safeguarding the country's territorial integrity "in
the best possible manner," he said.
</P>
<P>
Integration into the EU and NATO remains a key foreign policy
priority for Bulgaria, said National Assembly Chairman Sokolov.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria is not hostile to Yugoslavia and is not getting
involved in the Kosovo conflict, Kostov stressed.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the Rambouillet agreement would keep the
present borders of Yugoslavia, which would be good for Bulgaria,
he said.
</P>
<P>
A different solution would reshape the borders in the Balkans
which, he said, would destabilize the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
