<HEADLINE> Kuwait Minister Relieved Over Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Oil Minister Saud
Nasser Al-Sabah said Monday he was relieved over the present oil
price hikes following the recent output cuts by the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
The prices are improving in the right and desirable direction,
Saud told Kuwait News Agency during the foundation laying ceremony
for a catalyst plant.
</P>
<P>
The average price of OPEC's basket of seven crudes reached
14.83 U.S. dollars per barrel last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that oil prices in the world market
would further climb up after the usual summer slump.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti official noted that the ascending oil prices is
proof that oil producing countries are committed to their pledged
cuts.
</P>
<P>
"We are closely watching the markets and waiting for reports by
month end that will show the degree of commitment to cuts in
exports by other countries," Saud said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, OPEC members agreed to slash production by 1.7
million barrels per day (bpd).
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, a Gulf emirate with a crude reserve of near 100
billion barrels, began on April 1 an output reduction of 140,000
bpd from its former level of 1.98 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
A number of non-OPEC oil producers also agreed to cut
productions by 400,000 bpd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
