<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Cigars, Pipes as Lethal as Cigarettes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Cigars and pipes are just as
lethal as cigarettes, the World Health Organization (WHO) said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cigars and pipes, long promoted by the tobacco industry as
status symbols or glamorous cousins of the humble cigarette, cause
cancer and kill just as cigarettes do, the WHO cited a new
European study by the International Agency for Research on Cancer
(IARC) as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The writing on the wall is clear: the time has come to apply
the same controls used for cigarettes to cigars and pipes," said
Dr Derek Yach, head of the WHO Tobacco Free Initiative.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the Lyon-based IARC study, Yach said that the study
is a message for "politicians, fashion models, movie stars and
sports people who glamorize and popularize cigars and pipes by
endorsing these products or smoking them in public."
</P>
<P>
The IARC conducted the study in seven centers in Germany, Italy
and Sweden. The three-country study included 5,621 men with lung
cancer who were compared to 7,255 men without lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
Cigar smokers were nine times more likely to develop lung
cancer than non-smokers, according to the study. Pipe-smokers ran
an almost eight-fold risk of getting lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
Lower rates of lung cancer among cigar and pipe smokers are
attributable to the fact that pipe and cigar smokers consume less
tobacco on average than cigarette smokers, and not because cigars
and pipe tobacco are less harmful, the study said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Prime Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit announced here Monday evening that he had submitted his
resignation to President Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit resigned after he learned the results of Sunday's local
and parliamentary elections in which his central-left Democratic
Left Party (DSP) took the lead.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said that Demirel asked him to continue his minority
coalition government until the new, 57th government is formed.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit became the prime minister of the 56th government in
January after the government led by Mesut Yilmaz lost a
confidence vote in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Yilmaz government collapsed last November because of
corruption scandals.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit's DSP led the elections by winning 21.76 percent of over
37 million votes cast in the local and the 21st parliamentary
elections on Sunday. The DSP will gain 134 deputies in the
550-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit is expected to hold talks with other political party
leaders on the formation of a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister won more support from the people than
expected, partly as the result of the capture of Abdullah Ocalan,
leader of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in Kenya in
mid-February.
</P>
<P>
The DSP secured support from voters in big cities such as
Istanbul, Ankara and Izmir. But it lost support in southeastern
Turkey where most Kurdish people are populated.
</P>
<P>
About 85 percent of the voters turned out in the elections
across Turkey and this was the first time in Turkey that the local
and parliamentary elections were held at the same date.
</P>
<P>
The right-wing National Movement Party (MHP) ranked second in
the elections by gaining 18.40 percent of the votes and will
occupy 129 seats in the parliament. This marked a surprising rise
of support among the voters.
</P>
<P>
The MHP won support from young people and from many who had
supported the pro-Islamic Virtue Party (FP), which has won only
15.14 percent of the votes and will have 109 deputies in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The FP had reportedly fought a battle for the number one spot
in Sunday's elections but apparently failed to sustain its glamour
during the last elections.
</P>
<P>
Due to the long discord between the central-right Motherland
Party (ANAP) led by former Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and the
central-right True Path Party (DYP) led by former Prime Minister
Tansu Ciller, the two parties got less support from the people by
winning only 13.57 percent and 12.82 percent of the votes
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The ANAP will have 86 deputies and the DYP 90 deputies in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Republican Peoples' Party (CHP) won 8.48 percent of the
votes and it can not enter into the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Under the Turkish election law, a political party should enter
into the parliament by winning at lest 10 percent of the votes in
general elections.
</P>
<P>
In the last general election in December 1995, the now-defunct
pro-Islamic Welfare Party (RP), predecessor of the FP, took the
lead by winning 21.23 percent of the votes, followed by the ANAP
with 19.66 percent of the votes, the DYP with 19.20 percent, the
DSP with 14.65 percent and the CHP with 10.75 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
