<HEADLINE> Combat 18 Admits London Bomb Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- A man claiming to be from the
extreme right-wing group Combat 18 told police Monday they were
responsible for the bomb attack in south London Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The call was made from a telephone box on Well Hall Road, south
London -- near where Stephen Lawrence was murdered in April 1993.
</P>
<P>
But Scotland Yard detectives say they were keeping an open mind
about the motive behind Saturday afternoon's attack which injured
48 people and have not ruled out the phone call being a hoax.
</P>
<P>
Police are still sifting through recordings from nearby
security cameras to see if the bomber was caught on video.
</P>
<P>
Of the 48 people injured in the blast, 14 are still in
hospital, with four giving doctors cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
Two men, being treated in King's College Hospital, may lose
their sight.
</P>
<P>
Detectives are still examining possible motives for the bomb
attack as they step up their hunt for the culprit.
</P>
<P>
The Brixton street where the bomb blasted remains cordoned off,
but police say it will be reopened as soon as the shops which line
both sides had been made secure. Many still have broken windows.
</P>
