<HEADLINE> COMESA Members Urged to Export Finished Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has urged member states of
the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) to
increase the export volume of their finished products to enhance
economic growth and development in the region.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Minister of Commerce, Trade and Industry, David Mpamba,
said in Lusaka Monday when opening the Fourth Meeting of COMESA
Trade and Customs Committee that the region had the capacity to
convert raw materials into finished goods for export as a major
source of income.
</P>
<P>
"It is about time we thought of pursuing exportation of goods
to countries outside COMESA," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian minister said that member states would find it
easier to remove customs duty as they would concentrate on
importing raw materials for the manufacturing of finished products
for export.
</P>
<P>
He urged COMESA members to urgently eliminate all types of
barriers to regional trade and development.
</P>
<P>
The fear by some governments that they would loose revenue by
reducing tariffs was unfounded, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mpamba noted that countries and global groupings were moving
away from dependence on customs duties as the major source of
their income to more neutral taxes such as value added tax (VAT)
and sales tax.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed gratitude that 16 member states out of
the 21 had reduced import duties on COMESA products by between 60
to 90 percent while almost all members had removed the classical
non-tariff barriers.
</P>
<P>
Mpamba also urged COMESA members to support the development of
cross- border trade because it was a source of income to the
region's unemployed people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
