<HEADLINE> Asia First Included into McDonald's Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 19 (Xinhua) -- A league champion from Asia
gained the first entrance into the prestigious 1999 McDonald's
Championship to be held in Milan in October, Carl Ching Men-ky,
president of Asian Basketball Confederation (ABC) announced on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Basketball in Asia is on its way, and a new era is beginning,
" Carl Ching Men-ky told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
The McDonald's Championship is also called the World Basketball
Club Championship, created by world basketball governing body FIBA
and the NBA in 1987.
</P>
<P>
"We are thrilled that finally an Asian team will be represented
in Milan, along with the top club teams from around the world. Now
we can say that the McDonald's Championship is a world
championship of professional leagues, " said Ms. Mary Reiling
Spencer, vice president and managing director of NBA Asia Pacific.
</P>
<P>
"This is a historic day for Asian basketball. We are honored
to have an Asian team participate for the first time ever in this
prestigious tournament. It speaks volume of the strength and
maturity of our basketball development in Asia, " said ABC
Secretary General Yeoh Choo Hock, who has been lobbying FIBA for
the instatement of the Asian side for several years.
</P>
<P>
The event was expanded from the original three-team format to
four teams from 1988 to 1991, and in 1993 it grew to its current
six-team format. Since 1991, the championship has been scheduled
to compliment the Olympics and the World Championship on the four-
year international basketball calendar.
</P>
<P>
The event features the best clubs in the world. Competitions in
the Euroleague, ABC Champions cup, the national basketball league
in Australia and the South American Basketball league are in the
process of crowning club champions that will go on to compete for
this year's McDonald's championship title.
</P>
<P>
The Chicago Bulls won the last title in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
