<HEADLINE> S. Africa Launches Youth-Oriented Anti-Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 19 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela Monday launched a campaign to steer the youth from
crime.
</P>
<P>
The campaign would use former prisoners to teach the youth that
crime did not pay. Young people would also be trained to become
leaders in the program.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said the initiative deserves the support of all South
Africans.
</P>
<P>
"By combining education and crime prevention, by working in our
schools and among our young people who are unemployed or in
prison, the campaign will indeed bring the light of hope," he said
at a ceremony in Midrand, north of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said the time to blame all the country's difficulties
on the past has long gone. But he said apartheid had corroded the
moral fabric of society and left a legacy of poverty that would
take years to eradicate.
</P>
<P>
While the underlying causes of crime such as poverty and
inequality should be addressed, tough action against criminals
should continue by enforcing stricter laws and bail conditions, he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Those who commit crime must know they will be caught and
punished," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the government's repeated commitments to curb crime,
the crime wave seems to be spiralling.
</P>
<P>
Last week, quite a few incidents sparked outrage. A Soweto
principal and a photographer were murdered and a U.N. official was
raped. The Burundian ambassador to South Africa, Gedeon Magete,
was robbed for a second time within seven days. 
</P>
