<HEADLINE> Most of Zambia's State Enterprises Privatized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- About 86 percent of state-owned
enterprises in Zambia had been privatized by the end of March, the
Zambian Privatization Agency (ZPA) said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued by the agency, out of the
280 state- run enterprises in its working portfolio, 242 have been
privatized since the agency was established in 1992.
</P>
<P>
As the winding up of the country's privatization program,
donors have resumed financial aid by releasing a total of 36
million U.S. dollars so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The donors withheld their promised balance-of-payment support
to Zambia last year because of the delayed privatization of the
country's copper mines.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Anglo-American Corporation and Zambia signed a
memorandum of understanding over the sale of Nchanga, Nkana and
Konkola mines of the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines, paving the
way for the resumption of the aid.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian Privatization Agency is expected to end its mission
before the end of next year, according to the press release.
</P>
