<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli President to Visit Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 19 (Xinhua) -- President Ezer Weizman will pay
a short visit to Egypt Thursday at the invitation of his Egyptian
counterpart Hosni Mubarak, Israel Radio said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The radio did not elaborate on the upcoming visit. But the
stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace process and the Palestinian
statehood are expected to be on the agenda of the talks between
the two presidents.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the Palestinian statehood has drawn worldwide
attention as May 4, the date when the five-year interim period for
Palestinian self-government expires, is around the corner.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat has
traveled around the world in the last two months to garner support
for the Palestinian right to statehood and to collect suggestions
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
He has been urged by most of the countries he visited,
including the United States, to delay a unilateral declaration
planned on May 4 so as not to further derail the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Peace-making between Israel and the Palestinians has been in
stalemate since Israel froze the implementation of the Wye
agreement signed last October.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian Central Council, a 125-member Palestinian
leadership body, will meet next week to make a final decision on
this issue.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has reportedly favored a delay in the declaration.
</P>
<P>
Weizman, a strong pursuer of peace with Arab neighbors, has
said that a unilateral declaration of statehood by Arafat is
"unwise."
</P>
<P>
Although also famed for his record as a warrior, Weizman helped
forge the Jewish state's ground-breaking peace treaty with Egypt
in 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
