<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Park Attracts More Tourists After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Bwindi Impenetrable Forest
National Park in southwestern Uganda, a place known to the world
after eight foreign tourists were killed there in March this year,
has attracted more tourists after it reopened to tourism
activities in early April.
</P>
<P>
So far, the park has received some 80 foreign tourists from
Germany, Sweden, England, Australia, Switzerland and Canada, Radio
Uganda reported Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Lillian Adarova, a visitor service coordinator with Uganda
Wildlife Authority, was quoted as saying that the Ugandan
government has put in place enough security measures to ensure the
safety of the tourists.
</P>
<P>
The Second Division Commander Benon Biraro assured the tourists
and the public at large that the government army will maintain its
presence in the area at all times.
</P>
<P>
The national park became internationally well-known after eight
foreign tourists were killed on March 1 by the Interahamwe rebels
allegedly coming from eastern part of the Democratic Republic of
Congo.
</P>
<P>
This massacre has plunged the young tourism industry in Uganda
to a record low.
</P>
<P>
With deployment of troops around the park and improvement of
telecommunications facilities in the area, more visitors came to
visit the park which is home to some 300 mountain gorillas, more
than half of its total population in the world, the report said..
</P>
<P>
Mountain gorilla tracking is the most lucrative activity the
park offers. It accounts for some 70 percent of the Uganda
Wildlife Authority's annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
Since the number of tourists entering the park to track
gorillas is limited, many foreign tourists have to book their
tickets one year in advance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
