<HEADLINE> Iraq Slams U.S. Comment on Algerian Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Monday slammed the
comment of the United States on Algeria's presidential election as
"irresponsible" and a "flagrant interference in Algeria's internal
affairs."
</P>
<P>
An unnamed Iraqi foreign ministry spokesman said in a
statement carried by the Iraqi News Agency that the U.S. comment
has "ulterior motives" aimed at harming Algeria's security and
reputation.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman said the U.S. was disappointed
at the process of Algeria's presidential election, alleging that
fraud votes were found, and that six candidates withdrew from the
election in order to help the single remaining candidate win the
election.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman affirmed Iraq's support to the Algerian
people and their leaders, adding Iraq "opposes any form of foreign
interference in Algeria's internal affairs."
</P>
<P>
The Algerian government announced Friday morning that Abdelaziz
Bouteflika, the single remaining presidential candidate, won the
election with 73.79 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
The turnout rate cited by the Algerian government stood at 60
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
