<HEADLINE> Y2K Bug May Eat into Food Supply System, U.N. Warns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The year 2000 millennium
bug may have a negative impact on world food supply system
especially in developing countries, a U.N. agency warned on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) said
those countries relying on food aid while lacking funds to solve
the Y2K problem are among the vulnerables.
</P>
<P>
The Rome-based FAO said the bug, regarded as a factor to cause
chaos in the global computer system by not distinguishing between
1900 and 2000 if it not properly fixed, may threaten to affect all
of supplies and services essential to agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
The FAO called on developing countries to look for alternative
ways for safe food deliveries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
