<HEADLINE> Kenya Bars Sugar Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Sugar Authority (KSA)
announced here Monday it would impose a three-month ban on
imported sugar in the east African country until local
manufacturers sell out all their stocks.
</P>
<P>
The only exception will be sugar imported by legally registered
 companies for industrial use, the government agency said.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the KSA Mark Too said any sugar imported would be
held in warehouses until the local sugar companies run out of
stocks.
</P>
<P>
Too said the curb on sugar imports was part of KSA's efforts to
 streamline sugar importation and warehousing in the country.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Kenya Sugar-cane Growers Association complained
that massive imports of white sugar were threatening local
companies, citing that 88,600 tons of domestic sugar worth 3.6
billion shillings (about 57 million U.S. dollars) would go to
waste due to the imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
