<HEADLINE> Wall Street's Strides Spur European Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Driven by early strides on Wall
Street and gains in the oil and pharmaceutical sectors, share
prices in Europe's main stock markets jumped 1.4 to 2 percent
higher Monday with London at its new record.
</P>
<P>
The UK's FTSE 100 leading index ended 94.7 points, or 1.47
percent higher, at 6515.3, two points above its previous record
close last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Oil giant Shell, raced ahead 3.1 percent to 445 pence, while
BP/Amoco barreled up more than 5 percent, to close at 1159 pence
in London.
</P>
<P>
The gains were supported by solid evidence on the market that
OPEC producers were implementing a large portion of the 1.7
million bpd of output cuts they pledged in March.
</P>
<P>
Frandfurt's Xetra DAX index closed at 5252.40, up 109.38 from
Friday's close. Meanwhile the floor traded Dax index, closed up
64.80 at 5220.
</P>
<P>
Karstadt was the day's strongest gainer at 406.50 euro, up
40.50, or 11.06 percent, after it announced a merger with
Schickedanz' mail order unit Quelle.
</P>
<P>
French share prices closed higher as sharp gains in early Wall
Street trading prompted a flurry of buying activity shortly ahead
of the French market close.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 index of leading components finished up 1.82
percent, at 4370.34, a new 1999 closing record. 
</P>
</TEXT>
