<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Opposes U.N. Mandate to Use Force in Yugoslavia: Vedrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine said on Tuesday that Russia always opposes the approval by
the United Nations for a use of force in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Russia has expressed its opposition at the U.N. Security
Council to a French proposal to use Chapter Seven of the U.N.
Charter to justify a deployment of foreign troops in Kosovo, said
Vedrine at the French National Assembly, or lower house of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
"For the moment, the Russians don't want to vote a resolution
in the name of Chapter Seven. They don't want to overstep the
line toward a resort to force," he said.
</P>
<P>
France wishes to use Chapter Seven of the U.N. Charter, which
justifies international action to stop violence endangering a
whole people, to give a legal basis to NATO intervention against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
But the French foreign minister said that France will continue
to seek cooperation from Russia for a political and diplomatic
solution to Kosovo in future.
</P>
<P>
While ruling out any possibility for Kosovo to win independence,
Vedrine said that the idea on international protection in the
Yugoslav province is gaining ground and it will make a U.N.
involvement indispensable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
