<HEADLINE> India Rejects U.S. Demands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- India Tuesday rejected as
unacceptable the United States demands that any new regime in
India should accept international demands on nuclear and missiles
issues.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen the comment attributed to the U.S. State
Department spokesman. We believe that it is not appropriate to
make such pronouncements on the course of a process of democratic
transition," said a spokesman of the External Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said earlier in
Washington that the United States wanted India to take concrete
steps as soon as possible to respond to the non-proliferation
demands of the international community.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also said that the United States strongly supported the
Lahore process and hoped India would move fast on the Lahore
Declaration signed between prime ministers of India and Pakistan
last February.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question of so-called non-proliferation demands,"
the Indian official spokesman said, adding that New Delhi would
not accept any such demands.
</P>
<P>
As for India-Pakistan issues, the spokesman said that there was
a bilateral process underway, which would continue. 
</P>
