<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Bulgarians Against Opening Territorial Air to NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A late poll shows that 63 percent
of Bulgarians oppose granting the use of Bulgarian airspace for
NATO's military operation against Yugoslavia, Now newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, which surveyed 623 people, followed a request by NATO
made Saturday for unlimited access to Bulgaria's airspace.
</P>
<P>
Only 24 percent of the people approved of NATO's request.
Thirteen percent did not comment on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that 72 percent of those polled were worried
that Bulgaria would risk involvement in a war if it opened its air
corridor to the Western alliance. Half of the people thought the
risk was high.
</P>
<P>
Sixty percent of the people disapproved of Bulgarian President
Petar Stoyanov's position to provide all possible help to NATO and
only 22 percent agreed with him. This is the lowest support rate
for the president since he took office two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Under Bulgaria's constitution, foreign armed forces cannot pass
through the country unless the Bulgarian parliament gives its
approval. The Constitutional Court ruled in 1994 that each case
would require separate parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian parliament is due to vote on NATO's request on
Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's opposing Socialist Party has clearly expressed
objection to NATO's request.
</P>
<P>
The majority of Bulgarian people are predominantly Slav
Orthodox population. Serbians have held rallies throughout the
country against the request.
</P>
<P>
However, Prime Minister Ivan Kostov, Parliamentary Speaker
Yordan Sokolov as well as Stoyanov have all agreed to give grant
to NATO's request, according to the local media.
</P>
<P>
The parliament, in which Kostov's center-right Union of
Democratic Forces has a clear majority, is very likely to approve
the request. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
