<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bouteflika Proclaimed President of Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Abdelaziz Bouteflika was formally
proclaimed president of the Republic of Algeria on Tuesday by the
Constitutional Council of Algeria, after his victory in the
presidential election on April 15.
</P>
<P>
Constitutional Council President Said Bouchair made the
announcement on television, according to reports from Algiers.
</P>
<P>
Bouteflika won 7,445,045 votes, or nearly 74 percent of the
votes cast, Bouchair reportedly quoted verified figures released
by the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The new president will take over the position from his
predecessor, Liamine Zeroual, after being sworn in on Saturday,
said Algerian newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The six other presidential candidates withdrew from the vote in
the last minute to protest what they called "fraud in primary
voting operations" among Saharan nomadic people and in military
barracks.
</P>
<P>
But the opposition candidates still won 26 percent of the votes,
with moderate Islamist Ahmed-Taleb Ibrahimi winning 1,265,594
votes, Abdallah Djaballah 400,080 votes, Hocine Ait-Ahmed 321,179
votes, Mouloud Hamrouche 314,160 votes, Mokdad Sifi 226,139 votes
and Youssef Khatib 121,414 votes.
</P>
<P>
The participation rate stood at 60,25 percent of a total of 17,
488,759 registered voters in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
This was disputed by the opposition parties, who estimate it at
between 20 and 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bouteflika will be the fifth president of Algeria since the
country's independence in 1962 from France, after Ahmed Benbella,
Houari Boumediene, Chadli Bendjedid and Liamine Zeroual.
</P>
<P>
Zeroual became the first democratically elected president in
1995 by beating three rivals from the opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Algeria was governed by a five-man presidency council from
January 1992 -- after the military canceled a legislative election
result which let Islamists come to power -- till January 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
