<HEADLINE> Romania Grants Use of Airspace to NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Romania's Supreme Defense
Council, the country's highest institution in charge of national
security, decided Tuesday to grant the recent request of NATO for
unlimited access to Romania's airspace.
</P>
<P>
NATO made the request to enhance its military operations
against Yugoslavia on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
President Emil Constantinescu, who chaired the meeting of the
Supreme Defense Council, will present the request to the
parliament for a vote, the presidential press office announced.
The parliament is the only institution mandated to make a decision
on such issues, according to the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The president consulted with leaders of various parties on this
matter before the meeting.
</P>
<P>
NATO's request did not include the use of Romanian airports or
other ground facilities by NATO aircraft for their flights to
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
NATO aircraft currently have access to Romania's air space only
in "emergency and unforeseen situations" under a ruling the
Romanian Parliament made in October last year following a NATO
request. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
