<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Vows To Succeed In Strikes Before Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) expressed its "firm stand" again here Tuesday
for carrying on the military campaign against Yugoslavia to the
end as there are two days before the alliance's 50th anniversary
celebration in Washington this week.
</P>
<P>
Both British Prime Minister Tony Blair and NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana told reporters here after their
meeting that the 19-nation alliance's determination was firm.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that his meeting with Blair gave them "a further
opportunity to consider the Kosovo crisis. "I can speak for both
of us when I stress once again our, and the alliance's, firm
determination to succeed. We will stand firm to the end."
</P>
<P>
Blair also said when answering questions that the solution of
the NATO strikes is "very simple:" "we carry on until he (Mr.
Milosevic) does step down."
</P>
<P>
Asked if NATO has any further plan about deployment of ground
troops in Kosovo since the prime minister met with the Hungarian
foreign minister on that last week, Blair said NATO was very
grateful for the help that Hungary had given and the support in
circumstances where they were aware, but he refused to reveal
anything about ground troops.
</P>
<P>
"What we must now demonstrate, over the next coming period of
time, is constantly to restate the basic reasons why we are, where
we are, constantly to emphasize that our demands and objectives
are reasonably met in full," Blair told reporters at NATO
headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
A NATO civilian spokesman, Jamie Shea, told a daily news
briefing Tuesday afternoon that Solana also, by telephone, talked
with the prime ministers of Norway, the Netherlands and Luxembourg
as part of his ongoing consultations to prepare for the Washington
summit. "They also reviewed the latest development in Kosovo," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
