<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Study Antarctica's Highest Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have climbed
to the highest point of the South Pole, 3,910 meters above sea
level and carried out the first ever scientific investigations in
the region during their 15th expedition to Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
Scientists drilled ice cores to a total depth of more than 200
meters and obtained a large number of snow and air samples in this
highest region of the Antarctic ice cap during the 50-day
expedition from December 15 to February 3, according to a press
conference here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
There was no human contamination of the ice cores and snow
samples which will provide precious data for research into global
climate changes, said scientists from the Lanzhou Institute of
Glaciology and Cryopedology under the Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS).
</P>
<P>
The Antarctic ice cap, covering a total area of over 13 million
square kilometers, is the largest glacier on earth and contains 70
percent of the earth's fresh water.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists traversed more than 1,100 kilometers on the
ice cap, the longest trek in the region's history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Expands Telephone Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Ministry of
Transport and Communications said Tuesday the country's telephone
lines have been more than quadrupled in recent seven years, from
150,000 to 650,000.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, Acting Minister of Transport and
Communications Mohamoud Dirir said his ministry is heading towards
the target of 720,000 telephone lines by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Mohamoud said the Ethiopian Telecommunications Corporation,
which presently employs a blend of technologies like the
micro-wave and satellite system has bought 470 V-SATs.
</P>
<P>
This shall, he said, effectively serve the rural communities in
the remotest areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
The acting minister added the mobile cellular phone shall be
introduced in Ethiopia very soon, adding that "we shall begin with
20,000 terminals to serve subscribers in Addis Ababa and its
environs."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the internet service which has only 2,400
subscribers now, the acting minister said that "with a modest
grant from the U.N. Development Program to the Ethiopian
Telecommunications Corporation to seek a solution to the problem
of congestion in the internet, we shall soon be able to serve
14,000 subscribers." 
</P>
</TEXT>
