<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Model of Design for Reunification Monument Displayed in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A model of the design for
Reunification Monument was displayed to the public here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Selected from a total of 260 submissions through open
invitation and approved by Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), the outstanding
design is adopted as the basis of design concept for the monument.
</P>
<P>
According to the design, the monument is composed of three
parts: the pedestal, the pillar and the head, with a total height
of about 20 meters and a width of 1.6 meters.
</P>
<P>
The name of the monument as written by President Jiang Zemin
will be engraved on the facade of the pillar and the Chinese and
English versions of the inscription separately on the east- and
west-facing sides of the pedestal.
</P>
<P>
The bottom part of the pillar is square in shape and is
gradually rounded off towards the top. It is made up of 206
overlapping stone slabs, each of which representing a year between
1842 and 2047. A glass ring with built-in lighting marks the
return of Hong Kong to China in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Leung Chun-ying, chairman of the Working Group on Reunification
Monument, said at a press conference here Tuesday the estimated
construction cost, including costs on advanced and ancillary works,
amounts to 9.68 million HK dollars (1.24 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The monument will be temporarily erected to the north-west of
the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center Extension where the
handover ceremony was held.
</P>
<P>
Upon the completion of the proposed new HKSAR government
headquarters at the former Tamar site, the HKSAR government might
consider relocating the monument permanently to the open space off
the new headquarters for better coordination in the celebration
for the anniversary of the HKSAR establishment and other relevant
functions.
</P>
<P>
According to suggestions raised by the working group, the
Government House will be renamed as "Zilu" in Chinese. Zi refers
to Bauhinia, the city flower of Hong Kong while Lu means a
unpretentious cottage.
</P>
<P>
The new Chinese name will be formally adopted with effect from
July 1, 1999 while the English name "Government House" will remain
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Set up on July 1, 1998, the working group openly invited
submissions of monument design, monument inscription and new names
for the government House between September 28 and November 14 last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
