<HEADLINE> Britain Sends More Troops to Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Britain is sending another batch
of 2,000 soldiers to Macedonia, raising the total number of
British troops in the Balkan country to 6,300.
</P>
<P>
A Macedonian news agency MIA report, monitored here Tuesday,
said that the new batch of British soldiers will start arriving in
one week.
</P>
<P>
The MIA quoted a spokesman for the NATO troops in Macedonia as
saying that a group of German soldiers, mostly engineers, have
already moving in from Greece.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recent incidents of NATO planes dropping what
were termed as "objects" in north Macedonia, the spokesman, Eric
Mognot, admitted that three objects have fallen down from the NATO
planes flying over Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
"An investigation is under way, " he said while stressing that
no property damage was reported by the fallen objects.
</P>
<P>
A separate MIA report said that a pilotless aircraft crashed
Sunday at 17:00 o'clock local time near the Jegunovce village in
Macedonia's Tetovo County.
</P>
<P>
Local policemen, who rushed to the site of crash, said that the
aircraft was bearing German marks.
</P>
<P>
The Macedonian side has informed the German post of the NATO
forces in the county of the accident, the Macedonian Information
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Macedonia reaffirmed on Monday that Macedonia will
not allow NATO troops to launch a possible ground offensive
against Yugoslav troops in Kosovo from its soil.
</P>
<P>
Macedonian Defense Minister Nikola Kljusev said, "Macedonia's
position is that its territory is not to be used for attacking
other countries." 
</P>
