<HEADLINE> Becker quits Monte Carlo Open after father dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- German tennis star Boris Becker
quit the Monte Carlo Open on Tuesday after his father death,
according to reports.
</P>
<P>
Karl-Heinz Becker, 63, died in a clinic in Heidelberg on Monday
night after a long fight against cancer.
</P>
<P>
"I am very sad, I admired my father and I owe him a lot,"
Becker was quoted as saying. "In this difficult situation, I have
to and want to be close to my family. Especially my mother needs
me."
</P>
<P>
Reports said Becker, who entered the tournament on invitation,
had reached the second round by beating Frenchman Cedric Pioline
on Monday and was due to take on another French player Jerome
Golmard.
</P>
<P>
Becker last week came back from Asia, withdrawing before the
Japan Open after reaching the final in Hong Kong when his father's
condition worsened.
</P>
<P>
Becker, 31, is determined to retire after a final fling at
Wimbledon this summer, followed by a farewell to Stuttgart in July
at the Mercedes Cup, reports said. 
</P>
