<HEADLINE> Arab Ministers Meet on Higher Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Education ministers from 21
Arab nations began a three-day meeting in the Saudi capital of
Riyadh Tuesday on priorities for higher education and scientific
researches in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which is titled "Higher Education and Scientific
Research in Confronting Challenges of the 21st Century", will
also tackle issues of enhancing information networks in Arab
countries as well as finding mechanisms for marketing results
of scientific researches to serve the development of the Arab
community.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Arab League Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization, Mohammad Al-Mili said at the opening
session that the Arab higher education ministers conference has
become a pan-Arab institution contributing in reforming higher
education, supporting scientific research and solving main issues
in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Saudi Minister of Higher Education Dr. Khalid
Al-Ankari stressed in his inaugural speech the importance of
preserving Arab identity in order not to be overwhelmed by
world cultures.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ankari said Arab education establishment has an important
role in producing an Arab personality with self-immunity.
</P>
<P>
He said "Arab universities will not be able to shoulder
the responsibility only through the care of our Arab and Islamic
culture," urging Arab states to stress the use of Arabic as the
language of education in Arab Universities.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi official also called for a greater intention for
technical and applied researches and a follow up of developments.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the conference, a round table seminar
will be held to discuss the outflow of the Arab minds and
the appropriate mechanism to consolidate relations between them
and their countries, the Kuwait News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting are also representatives from the
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization
(Unesco), Arab Universities Union, Islamic Organization for
Culture, Education and Science and the Arab Education Bureau
for the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) Countries. 
</P>
