<HEADLINE> Russian, Pakistani Prime Ministers Meet on Balkan Crisis, Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif met his Russian counterpart Yevgeny Primakov Sunday
to discuss the Balkan crisis, the situation in South Asia and
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, the first Pakistani leader to visit Russia in 25 years,
reportedly signed a inter-governmental economic cooperation
agreement with Primakov.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said the outcome of the talks indicated that both
sides hoped to improve bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The changed situation in Asia and the world has made it
necessary for the two countries to develop good bilateral
relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Pakistan hold similar positions regarding many
international and regional issues, and, both sides believe the
idea of building a unipolar world should not be permitted to gain
the upper hand, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
To develop relations between Russia, Pakistan, China and India
is of great importance to stability and security in South Asia,
Primakov noted.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also called on countries which own nuclear
weapons, including Pakistan and India, to join relevant
nonproliferation treaties and stop nuclear tests in any form.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said his country will view Russia as an important
stabilization factor in the world and in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers have agreed to continue consultations
on issues of mutual interest, according to Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, who arrived in Moscow on Sunday for a three-day
official visit, will also meet Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
other senior officials. 
