<HEADLINE> Romania, Bulgaria Discuss NATO's Request for Access to Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu Tuesday consulted his Bulgarian counterpart Petar
Stoyanov by telephone regarding NATO's recent request for
unrestricted access for its aircraft in the two countries'
airspace.
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu said he had talked by telephone with Stoyanov
shortly before a meeting of Romania's Supreme Defense Council,
which was convened to evaluate NATO's request.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian president said Stoyanov proposed coordinating the
positions of the two countries regarding the request.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Bulgarian president, the government, and the
parliamentary majority have agreed to allow NATO's aircraft to use
the country's airspace, according to Bulagria's news agency BTA.
</P>
<P>
NATO last Saturday called on Bucharest authorities to grant "
unlimited" access of Romania's air space for its aircraft. The
request did not include the use of Romanian airports and other
ground facilities by NATO aircraft for their flights to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
NATO aircraft currently have access to Romania's air space only
in "emergency and unforeseen situations," under a ruling the
Romanian parliament made in October last year.
</P>
<P>
After consulting with Prime Minister Radu Vasile on Monday,
Constantinescu held separate consultations Tuesday with leaders of
the ruling coalition and opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Romania's Supreme Defense Council, the country's institution in
charge of national security, is currently holding a session which
will be followed by an extraordinary sitting of Romania's
government. If they agree, it will be filed with Romania's
parliament, the only institution mandated to make such a decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
