<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Resumed Land Auction in HK Achieves Good Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government's
first land sale in nearly a year has achieved encouraging results
by raising 1.49 billion HK dollars (19 million U.S. dollars) with
a total of over 26,000 square meters of government lots.
</P>
<P>
Both government officials and property developers said the
prices were higher than expected.
</P>
<P>
Three lots were put up for auction Tuesday at the Concert Hall
of Hong Kong Cultural Center, Tsim Sha Tsui.
</P>
<P>
Property developers reacted positively to the auction, which
was held for the first time since the government decided to
suspend land sales in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
After the auction, Herbert Leung, assistant director of the
Lands Department, who conducted the auction, said the lots have
been successfully sold out in an open and just manner and the
prices were decided by the market.
</P>
<P>
Leung said the aim of the sale is to provide steady supplies of
land to meet the market demand and achieve stable property market.
</P>
<P>
The government suspended its land sales program at the end of
June last year in an effort to stabilize the sharply falling
property prices which had been hit by the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Property prices plunged by about 50 percent after the regional
economic crisis forced interest rates to soar.
</P>
<P>
While the sharp fall in property prices might be good for home
buyers, it has hurt the citizens and has an impact on other
economic sectors in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Small and Medium-sized enterprises, accounting for more than 90
percent of firms in Hong Kong, usually use their properties as
mortgages to get loans from banks.
</P>
<P>
The plunging property prices made it difficult for them to get
the loans.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, land sales are a major source of the
government's incomes. Taking 1996 and 1997 for example, the income
from land sales accounted for about 13 percent of the government
incomes.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of land sales in the 1998-99 fiscal year ending
March would have reduced the government's income by 30 billion HK
dollars (3.85 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The decision to resume the land sales was announced on February
12. Government officials said the policy objective is to ensure
stability in the property market and provide sufficient land to
meet the long-term needs.
</P>
<P>
Over the past six months prices have edged up by about 10-15
percent, analysts say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
