<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Says Selective Capital Controls Bear Positive Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Defending its selective
capital control measures, Malaysia said Tuesday the measures
introduced from September 1 last year have increased the country's
external reserves by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Between September 1, 1998, and April 15, 1999, Malaysia's
external reserves totaled 28.2 billion U.S. dollars, equivalent to
financing 6.1 months of retained imports compared with just 20
billion U.S. dollars, equivalent to financing 3.8 months of
retained imports last August, according to Second Finance Minister
Mustapa Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
"The 50 percent increase is a proud achievement. No one can
cast any doubt on that achievement," he was quoted by the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama as saying in Parliament
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the relaxation of the selective capital controls
by imposing an exit tax on repatriated foreign capital since
February 15 had succeeded in attracting net inflows of capital
totaling 440 million ringgit (115.789 million U.S. dollars) to
date. Of the total capital inflows of 1,570 million ringgit
(413.157 million U.S. dollars), outflows amounted to 1,130 million
ringgit (297.368 million U.S. dollars), he added.
</P>
<P>
"Introduction of the exit tax had improved investor sentiment.
Net capital inflows are being monitored daily and Bank Negara
(State Bank) Malaysia keeps a record daily," he said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the saying that the capital controls had not worked
and that investor confidence had yet to return as "inaccurate", he
said indicators had shown that the Malaysian economy was sound and
recovering.
</P>
<P>
He said fund managers, international financial institutions and
rating agencies had changed the ratings on Malaysia to stable from
negative previously and had even forecast economic growth higher
than the 1.0 percent predicted by the Malaysian government.
</P>
<P>
He cited Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley's forecast of 2.0
percent growth for Malaysia this year and an even higher growth
forecast by the Institute of International Finance and Credit
Suisse of between 3.0 and 3.1 percent this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
