<HEADLINE> Workshop On AIDS/HIV,TB Control Strategies In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A four-day workshop aimed to map
out a framework for a common AIDS/HIV and TB control strategies in
Africa Tuesday started in Harare.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from Botswana, Gambia, Kenya, Malawi, Namibia, South
Africa, Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe are attending the
meeting organized by the World Health Organization (WHO) Regional
Office for Africa.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will discuss about the performance of the on-going
community based AIDS/TB care projects, review the adapted training
tools, guidelines and current practices in the management of
AIDS/HIV/TB and develop a draft regional framework for
strengthening the prevention and care of TB and people living with
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, acting Director of the Communicable
Disease Prevention and Control Division of WHO Regional Office for
Africa, Antoine Kabore said since the advent of the HIV/AIDS
epidemic, Africa has witnessed a massive increase in
zero-prevalence and death rates in all the sub- regions. This has
been paralleled by an equally steep rise in incidence rates for
tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, the two diseases have become one of the most devastating
public health crises in the African region at the close of this
century," Kabore said.
</P>
<P>
Africa registered two million of the 2.5 million AIDS-related
deaths that occurred globally in 1998, Kabore said.
</P>
<P>
For TB, 1.6 million new infectious cases are estimated to occur
each year in the region, with over 600,000 deaths. Over the last
two decades, case notification rates have increased from under 100
per 100,000 inhabitants to over 400 per 100,000 inhabitants in
some countries in Southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The rapid increase is largely due to the HIV/AIDS epidemic in
these countries, Kabore said.
</P>
<P>
Kabore noted, "despite the efforts made by several African
governments to intervene on these two diseases, there seems to be
hardly any decline in the incidence and transmission."
</P>
<P>
He called this meeting to try and put together from various
experiences, a framework that will assist the countries to begin
to make some progress in their efforts to contain this rapidly
growing dual epidemic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
