<HEADLINE> Indian, Bangladeshi Troops Exchange Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Seven people were killed and
five others injured in an exchange of fire between Indian and
Bangladeshi border troops on Monday in the border area of Narsari
Para in West Bengal, India's Border Security Force (BSF) said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Two BSF men and two Bangladeshi rifles personnel were among the
seven killed, the BSF said in a press release, adding that two
Bangladeshi civilians and an Indian civilian were also killed in
the incident.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) quoted the release as saying;
"Firing was stopped from Indian side at 18:00 pm (local time
Monday) while Bangladesh rifle continued firing till 1845 hours."
</P>
<P>
It said senior BSF officials from Calcutta, 1,460 km southeast
of here, had rushed to the spot to try to bring the situation
under control.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from Dhaka, the Bangladeshi capital,
quoting official sources as saying that Bangladeshi Home Secretary
Safiur Rahman talked to Indian High commissioner in Bangladesh Deb
Mukharji about the incident.
</P>
<P>
The BSF release alleged that two "Bangladeshi dacoits" armed
with guns tried to sneak into Indian territory at about 09:45 am
on Monday at Narsari Para, a border post, after crossing
Matabhanga river.
</P>
<P>
It also claimed that the "dacoits" opened fire and the Indian
side returned fire "in self-defense" and injured one of them.
</P>
<P>
The release also said that about 100 Bangladeshi nationals
gathered at the border and entered into Indian territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
