<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Central Bank Adjusts Monetary, Credit Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Reserve Bank of India (RBI),
the central bank of the country, adjusted its monetary and credit
policy Tuesday with a cut in the cash reserve ratio by 0.5 percent
to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The cut, which will be effective from May 8, would augment
banks' lendable resources by 32.5 billion rupees (approximately
773 million U.S. dollars), the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported
from Mumbai, India's financial capital, 1400 km southwest of here.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the monetary and credit policy for 1999-2000 at a
meeting with chairmen of commercial banks, RBI Governor Bimal
Jalan said the stance of monetary policy would continue to
facilitate adequate availability of liquidity along with stable
medium and long-term interest rate.
</P>
<P>
RBI would allowed banks to fix different prime lending rates
for different maturities and in keeping with the wishes of
industry, the central bank has permitted banks to offer fixed rate
loans.
</P>
<P>
RBI has also prescribed a ceiling of 10 percent of total
capital for banks and financial institutions for investment in
subordinated debt instruments.
</P>
<P>
As part of efforts at developing the money markets, RBI has
decided to permit money market mutual funds to offer "cheque
writing" facility to their investors through an arrangement with a
bank.
</P>
<P>
Jalan said that RBI and the central government would work out a
package to promote retail market for government securities.
</P>
<P>
In order to encourage flow of finance for venture capital, the
overall ceiling of five percent of incremental deposits on
investments by banks in shares, convertible debentures and units
of mutual funds would stand automatically enhanced to the extent
of banks' investment in venture capital.
</P>
<P>
RBI has with immediate effect withdrawn general refinance
facility to banks and replaced it with a collateralised lending
facility of up to 0.25 percent of the fortnightly average
outstanding aggregate deposits in 1997-98 for two weeks at the
bank rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
