<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Financial Reform Relevant to Asia Economic Recovery: Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said Tuesday the
reform of the international financial architecture (IFA) was
required as there was no guarantee that a financial turmoil like
the one which began in July 1997 would not recur.
</P>
<P>
Despite the signs of recovery shown by some crisis-hit Asian
economies, a revamp in the IFA remains a relevant issue, Second
Finance Minister Mustapa Mohamed told a press briefing here on
the forthcoming sixth APEC Finance Ministers' meeting to be held
in Malaysia next month.
</P>
<P>
The APEC finance ministers' meeting in Langkawi, a resort
island in northern Malaysia from May 15 to 16, will conduct a
follow-up on the reform issue and provide a momentum required to
get it resolved, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the APEC consultative efforts on the matter continue to
be important so as to avert the repeat of similar catastrophe in
the future.
</P>
<P>
As an informal consultative mechanism that brings together
leaders and ministers, the grouping is not in a position to play a
leading role on international financial issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
This role falls under the purview of the World Bank, the
International Monetary Fund (MF), the Group of Seven and the Group
of 22 countries, Mustapa said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said APEC had contributed to resolving the crisis
and had been successful as one of the avenues for Malaysia and
other developing economies to express and push forward various
agenda including the reform of the IFA.
</P>
<P>
He said as the message on the need for the reform filtered
through, there is now a convergence of views from other countries,
including industrialized ones in support for such reform. But
progress is lacking as there has been no concrete action so far,
he added.
</P>
<P>
At the Langkawi meeting, the ministers are expected to exchange
views on the economic and financial situation in the region
including prospects for recovery as well as the future work
programs aimed at strengthening APEC's economies and financial
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The ministers would also consider the finalization of various
initiatives now underway with focus on efforts to strengthen
financial systems and promote the return of stable and sustainable
private capital flows into the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
