<HEADLINE> ADB Provides Emergency Assistance Loan to Vanuatu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
Approved Tuesday an emergency assistance loan of 2 million U.S.
dollars for the Pacific nation of Vanuatu to repair infrastructure
damage caused by Cyclone Dani in January this year.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released Tuesday by the bank, the ADB's
loan will help the Vanuatu government to repair the country's
damaged infrastructure, which is seriously hindering tourism and
the transport of agricultural produce.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the rehabilitation program is estimated at
6.4 million U.S. dollars equivalent, of which the Vanuatu
government is financing 240,000 U.S. dollars. The European Union,
Australia, France, Japan and New Zealand are expected to
contribute 3.5 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ADB loan will come from its emergency rehabilitation
facility for small developing member countries and the repayment
period is 32 years, including a grace period of 8 years. 
</P>
