<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Investments of 161 million U.S.
dollars were attracted in oil and gas exploration last year in
Pakistan, a top petroleum official Tuesday said at an
international conference here.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Federal Minister for Petroleum and Natural Resources
Chaudhry Nisar Ali Khan told the third Pakistan Oil and Gas Summit
that 36 new exploration agreements were signed in the year 1997-98
(July-June) covering an area of 135,000 square kilometers which
was a record in one year.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan received investment commitments worth 1.2 billion
dollars in the upstream and downstream petroleum sectors last
year, he added.
</P>
<P>
Accelerated exploration activity resulted in 16 oil and gas
discoveries during the year, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
"Five of these gas discoveries are expected to add substantial
reserves of up to 5 to 6 trillion cubic feet resulting in an
increase of around 35 percent in our remaining reserves of natural
gas," Khan said.
</P>
<P>
He said a special focus was placed on offshore exploration and
an incentive package was introduced leading to the grant of first
ever exploration licence in deep waters last year.
</P>
<P>
The petroleum summit began on Tuesday and was attended by
representatives from Pakistani and international oil and gas
sector. 
</P>
