<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Lose $1.7 Billion over Mines Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will lose about 1.7 billion
U.S. dollars because of the selling of its remaining copper mines
to Anglo American Corporation (ACC) instead of the Kafue
consortium.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Mail weekly Tuesday quoted Theo Bull, chairman of
the Committee on Small Business Development of Zambia Association
of Chamber of Commerce and Industry (ZACCI), as saying that the
country will lose the money as the ACC offer for the remaining
mines of the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) is only 40
percent of the price that had been offered by the Kafue
consortium.
</P>
<P>
"A sale of the major mines at 40 percent of the value of the
promised investment we could have got two years ago from new
investors has many sad implications," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kafue's final bid submitted in May 1998 comprises cash of 130
million dollars, debt assumption of 35 million dollars, working
capital investment of 76 million, a five year capital investment
program of 708 million, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
ACC's bid of January 1999 comprises cash of 90 million dollars
without debt assumption and investment over three years of 300
million dollars representing a total commitment of 390 million
dollars for an 80 percent ownership, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"In simple arithmetical terms, the consortium's best bid at
1,060 million dollars for 88 percent share is roughly two and a
half times that of Anglo at 390 million dollars, 80 percent
share," he said.
</P>
<P>
He described the decision to refuse Kafue's offer as ill
advised and monumentally poor judgement.
</P>
<P>
Nchanga, Nkana and Konkola mines, which account for more than
two-thirds of Zambia's total copper mine assets, were sold to ACC
at the end of last year at 90 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
ACC has pledged to pump in 300 million dollars in three years
into the three mines of ZCCM.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government will retain a 20 percent share-holding
and establish a team to monitor ACC.
</P>
<P>
Due to disagreement over the cost of Nkana and Nchanga mines,
Zambia discontinued the negotiations with Kafue Consortium in
April last year over the sale of the two biggest mines in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In May last year, donors pledged to give the country an aid of
530 million dollars. However, they withheld the money to pressure
it to speed up the privatization of ZCCM. 
</P>
</TEXT>
