<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 48 Insurance Co.s Liquidated in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The National Insurance Commission
(NAICOM) of Nigeria is to revoke the licenses of 48 insurance
companies for non- compliance with statutory deposit payment to
the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN).
</P>
<P>
Out of the 48 companies, 19 are being shut down with immediate
effect while the other 29 will be effective from May 15, The
Guardian newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a sensitization of the insurance sector, only 29 companies
were cleared to engage in insurance business while 80 others were
placed on the waiting list for having paid the mandatory 50
percent of their paid-up share capital to the bank.
</P>
<P>
The Commissioner for Insurance, Chief Dipo Bailey, was quoted
as saying Monday that the process of clearance would continue
until May 15, adding certificates for final approval have been
given to those 29 companies while an additional list will be
published when more companies are cleared.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a consortium of 25 accounting companies has
been contracted to assess the solvency of approved insurers and to
prepare others for liquidation as part of the "on-going
sensitization of the insurance industry in line with international
standard".
</P>
<P>
The insurance chief ruled out a reprieve for affected
companies, saying the door was "officially closed" on the matter
at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
Under the Insurance Decree taking into effect in 1997, any
insurance company wishing to do business in Nigeria must deposit
with the bank 50 percent of its capital base.
</P>
<P>
The decree raised the capital base for insurance companies from
a minimum of 5 million naira (90 naira equal to one U.S. dollar)
to 20 million naira while at the same time pegging the maximum at
10 million naira to 90 million naira.
</P>
<P>
Since the promulgation of the decree, the deadline for
implementation of the decree has been extended twice as the hands
of NAICOM had all along been tied by the lingering court action
instituted against it by the underwriters under the aegis of the
Nigerian Insurance Association.
</P>
<P>
In its ruling last Wednesday, the Lagos High Court directed
insurance companies in the west African country to comply with the
decree by depositing 50 percent of their statutory capital base
with the bank.
</P>
<P>
There are 140 insurance companies, five reinsurance houses and
more than 50 brokerage companies operating in the most populous
African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
