<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A five-day record-breaking
streak on the Australian sharemarket came to an end Tuesday, with
the all ordinaries index closed lower.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index slipped 23.0 points to
3,090.1 points, just up from its intra-day trough of 3,088.2.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index eased 31.8 points to 5,453.1 and the
all resources index gave up some of its recent gains, shedding
19.2 points or 1.58 percent to 1,196.1 points.
</P>
<P>
"I think not only are we behaving after the Dow's performance
last night but we're trying to anticipate a down movement in the
Dow tonight," Henderson Charlton Jones adviser Stuart Smith said.
</P>
<P>
Smith said the distinct waves of overseas buying which had
driven resource stocks higher over recent days and fuelled the
surge in the all ordinaries was not evident in the market Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Among resource stocks, Australia's biggest industrial company
BHP surrendered 39 cents to 16.40 Australian dollars on turnover
of 8.6 million shares, and global miner Rio Tinto lost 15.7 cents
to 25.975 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the industrial sector, bank stocks had a mostly negative day
with the industry sub index diving 30.7 to 7,378.3 points.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank of Australia moved against trend, stacking on
20 cents to 28.50 Australian dollars, while National Australia
Bank shed 13.6 cents to 29.20 Australian dollars, ANZ bank fell
26.3 cents to 11.637 Australian dollars and Westpac bank eased two
cents to 11.60 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index added 3.7 to 1,035.0 points, and the spot price
of gold bullion in Sydney on Tuesday afternoon was 284.90 U.S.
dollars an ounce, compared to 284.55 U.S. dollars on Monday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 559.67 million stocks traded for 1.02
billion U.S. dollars. Falling stocks outnumbered rising stocks 790
to 668 and 499 stocks remained steady. 
</P>
