<HEADLINE> Nigeria Unfolds Schedule of Power Handing-over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's in-coming president and
state governors will take office on May 29 while Parliament
members and their counterparts in the states will be sworn in on
May 31 under a swearing-in schedule mapped out by the out-going
military regime.
</P>
<P>
All the elected officials have a four-year tenure except at the
council level of the local governments where the tenure is three
years, The Guardian newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The current military government of General Abdulsalami Abubakar
has given May 15 as deadline for the completion of all facilities
and structures to be used in regard of the leadership change-over.
</P>
<P>
A presidency source said at the weekend that 38 presidents and
heads of state had so far signified their intention to witness the
swearing-in ceremony of General Olusegun Obasanjo as the president
of Nigeria on May 29.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the Nigerian government has intensified
arrangements to receive the world leaders with major hotels in
capital Abuja booked "in their entirety" by the government for the
expected visit of the world leaders.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly or parliament Complex which will provide
office accommodation and conference chambers for the nation's 107
Senators and 360 House of Representatives members will be
completed and officially commissioned by Nigerian Head of State
Abubakar on May 15.
</P>
<P>
Federal Capital Territory Minister Major General Mamman
Kontagora has mounted pressure on the contractor Julius Berger to
complete the ground work ahead of time for "Eagle Square" where
the hand-over ceremony will take place.
</P>
<P>
The installation of all gadgets, especially communication
facilities at the "Eagle Square" and the National Assembly
Complex, will be completed before the deadline of May 15,
according to the minister. 
</P>
