<HEADLINE> Myanmar Cooperates With Thailand, Laos on Drug Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is making preparations to
join an upcoming meeting with Thailand and a trilateral
ministerial meeting among Myanmar, Thailand and Laos on
cooperation in eradication of narcotic drugs.
</P>
<P>
The meetings will be be held later this month in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
A preliminary meeting held here Monday was attended by Colonel
Tin Hlaing, Myanmar Minister of Home Affairs and chairman of the
Central Committee for Drug Abuse Control, and Colonel Thein Nyunt,
minister of Progress of Border Areas and National Races and
Development Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The meeting discussed implementation of the resolutions passed
by the 42nd meeting of U.N. Drug Control Program, the New Light of
Myanmar newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Thailand have been cooperating in drug control. The
anti-narcotics authorities of the two countries agreed at a
cross-border meeting in Tachilek in January this year to step up
drug suppression cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Also during a visit by Myanmar leader Senior-General Than Shwe
to Thailand last month, the two governments pledged to further
enhance their cooperation in the drug fight aimed at turning the
common border of the two countries into a border of friendship,
harmony and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Laos also cooperate in drug control. During Myanmar
Foreign Minister U Win Aung's visit to Laos last month, the two
sides signed an agreement on prevention of trafficking of drug and
psychotropic substances, and on control of banned chemical
substances.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar, Thailand and Laos, at their third
ministerial conference on cooperation in drug control held in
Vientiane in July 1997, agreed to cooperate in eradicating opium
poppy cultivation in the border areas and combating trafficking of
chemicals and materials for the production of narcotic drugs.
</P>
<P>
The three countries then also called for coordination among
their law enforcement agencies with exchange of information on
drug control measures and enacting laws and rules on drug abuse
control in the sub-region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
