<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Host Int'l Reproductive Health Expo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The '99 International
Reproductive Health and Family Planning Expo, sponsored by the
State Family Planning Commission (SFPC), will be held in Beijing,
the Chinese capital, in August.
</P>
<P>
Government organizations and enterprises from both at home and
abroad will introduce information and products related to
reproductive healthcare.
</P>
<P>
"China should focus on improving healthcare in conjunction with
controlling population growth," said SFPC Vice Director Yang Kuifu,
adding that the lack of knowledge related to reproductive health
is one of the major factors causing birth defects among new-born
babies in China.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has 130 million illiterate and semi-
illiterate citizens. The country thus has a large group of people
with inadequate healthcare knowledge to care themselves and their
children. More than 200,000 disabled infants are born in China
each year.
</P>
<P>
Incidence rates for sexually-transmitted diseases (STDs) and
HIV/AIDS are also on the rise, with 12,000 reported HIV cases and
417 AIDS patients nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Beijing hosted a national forum on population and resources in
March, with the central government using the event to stress the
urgent need to disseminate information in order to eradicate
ignorance concerning reproductive healthcare and reduce the
incidence rate for STDs.
</P>
<P>
The expo, scheduled for August 16-30, will also be held in
Shanghai, Dalian, Chongqing and Shenzhen if proven successful in
Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
