<HEADLINE> Share Prices Nosedown on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Share prices gyrated from
positive to negative territory on Singapore Stock Market Tuesday,
dragged down by some profit-taking encouraged by the weak
performance on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index plunged 32.83 points to
finish at 1,809.48 points.
</P>
<P>
The total volume decreased to 651.75 million units worth 979.22
million Singapore dollars (572.81 million U.S. dollars). Decliners
outnumbered advancers by 189 to 126 with 119 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The larger block was the 36.47 million stock parcel by Tuan S
which was transacted at 0.31 Singapore dollars per share. UIC was
the second most active mover with 18.26 million stocks done.
KimEng was the next with 18.05 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Transmarco headed the ascent of the day with a rise of 32 cents
to 2.86 Singapore dollars. Cerebos and OCBC picked up 20 cents to
finish at 3.88 and 10.20 Singapore dollars respectively. ST Comp
moved up 15 cents to finish at 1.42 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 was the biggest loser of the day
with a loss of 2.60 Singapore dollars to end at 22.70 Singapore
dollars. It was followed by Venture which shed 80 cents to close
at 9.20 Singapore dollars. CityDev retreated 70 cents to finish at
11.60 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted that the market finally relented to correction
after soaring up nearly 20 percent in March supported by fund
flows into the region from institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
The past two weeks saw a powerful liquidity run not seen since
the heady days of the last bull market in 1993.
</P>
<P>
As previous bull run rallies since the start of the Asian
crisis in July 1997 have proved short-lived, many market watchers
expected a correction although the market bullish behavior had
belied their expectation.
</P>
<P>
Dealers also said the disappointing figures released by
Singapore's Trade Development Board on the country's external
trade in March 1999 had somewhat affected the market sentiment and
accelerated profit-taking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
