<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Businessmen in HK Support China's Entry into WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of senior members
of the American Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong (AmCham) will
travel to Washington DC this weekend to pledge the support of the
American business community in Hong Kong for China's accession to
the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The AmCham said Tuesday it hopes to build on the momentum of
recent weeks as significant progress has been made on the WTO
talks.
</P>
<P>
"AmCham applauds the U.S. and Chinese negotiators for reaching
a breakthrough in their 13-year stalemate and is fully committed
to working with U.S. policy makers to overcome the remaining trade
obstacles preventing China's membership," said AmCham Chairman
Jason Felton.
</P>
<P>
AmCham's three-pronged strategy this year will be to expedite
China's WTO accession on commercially meaningful term; voice its
support for the renewal of the normal trade relations status for
China; and, once a successful WTO accord has been reached, will
lobby the U.S. Congress extensively to pass legislation that would
grant permanent normal trade relations status for China.
</P>
<P>
The AmCham delegation will be in Washington DC from April 26-30,
when meetings will be held with more than 150 senior
administration officials as well as members of the Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
