<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists: Kosovo War Hurts Euro Zone Economies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Though it's too early to count the
cost of NATO's attack on Yugoslavia, one early casualty is the
euro and a second could be consumer confidence in the 11-country
currency union, according to a Reuters survey of leading
economists.
</P>
<P>
The infant currency has been hitting record lows, beset by
worries over the Kosovo crisis. If the war is prolonged and
ground troops are sent in, consumer confidence could be the next
victim, dampening the euro zone's already weak growth prospects,
the Reuters quoted economists saying.
</P>
<P>
"The main negative could be through weaker consumer sentiment
which is the main linchpin holding up the economy," said Julian
Callow of Dresdner Kleinwort Benson in London. "The Gulf War led
to a mild U.S. recession; a nasty flare-up in the Balkans could
easily do the same for Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If consumer confidence goes, we're in trouble," said Daniel
Gros of the Center for European Policy Studies in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one out of 37 economists surveyed April 14-16 predicted
a protracted conflict would have a moderate impact on economic
growth while five thought it would be significant.
</P>
<P>
It could mean "greater deficits, higher interest rates, lower
growth rates and more instability", said ING Bank's Fred Pallada
in Amsterdam. Tourism revenues would also be hit, said Alison
Cottrell of PaineWebber in London. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
