<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Water Leaks Out At Indian Atomic Power Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- About six tons of heavy water
leaked out last month during inspection of a coolant channel tube
at an atomic power station in Madras, 2,090 km south of here, the
Press Trust of India (PTI) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some of the repair workers were exposed to excess tritium which
was said mildly radioactive, PTI said, quoting officials of
Nuclear Power Corporation of India (NPCIL).
</P>
<P>
A committee was set up to investigate the cause of the leak,
review the design of the special sealing plug used for inspection
from where the leak occurred and suggest remedial measures to
avoid recurrence of such incidents, NPCIL officials said.
</P>
<P>
The leak at Unit Two of the Madras Atomic Power Station on
March 26 was initially categorized as a "below scale" or "zero"
event in the international nuclear event scale which ranges from
zero to seven.
</P>
<P>
NPCIL officials said the incident was under review and the
rating of the incident was expected to be one.
</P>
<P>
They said the workers engaged in rectification of the leak wore
protective plastic suits to avoid tritium uptake and there was no
adverse effect on reactor safety during the incident, or abnormal
release of radioactivity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
