<HEADLINE> France Does Not Rule out NATO Ground Intervention in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- France said on Tuesday that a NATO
ground intervention against Yugoslavia is not excluded, but the
political objective of NATO, which is to stop violence against
Kosovars, remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
French Defense Minister Alain Richard said in an interview with
LCI television channel that "it is normal that we exclude nothing.
"
</P>
<P>
But he refused to give such kind of information which could "
help the adversary."
</P>
<P>
He said that NATO is prepared for "an entry on the ground by
the force of security, which is the necessary support to a
political solution."
</P>
<P>
About 12,000 NATO soldiers are deployed in Macedonia, waiting
for a peace agreement on Kosovo, he said.
</P>
<P>
The objective is to control the violence, he said, while
accusing Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic of "taking two
million people hostage."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said on
Tuesday that NATO will increase the number of targets to be struck
in the air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the U.S. newspaper International Herald
Tribune, Vedrine said that the objective of NATO airstrikes is to
"bring about a change to the regime of Serbia."
</P>
<P>
He said this objective is shared by not only Western countries,
but also Russia.
</P>
<P>
"The immediate objective of the bombings is to break the
military forces which the regime uses for the repression. Public
opinion understands these limits and supports our action," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
