<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Build Closer Ties With Russia: Sharif </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 20 -- Pakistani Prime Minister Mian Nawaz Sharif
said his country is ready to build closer relations with Russia,
Russian newspaper Izvestia reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the newspaper, Sharif, who arrived in
Moscow Monday for a three-day official visit, said the two
countries should work for a lasting all-round cooperative
relationship in accordance with the interests of both sides.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, the first Pakistani prime minister to visit Russia in
25 years, laid special emphasis on economic cooperation between
Pakistan and Russia, which he said has great potentials and should
precede cooperation in other areas.
</P>
<P>
He also called for close coordination between the two sides on
regional and global matters.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in South Asia, Sharif said the unresolved
Kashmir issue remains the cause of discord and tension between
Pakistan and India. The Pakistani government is exerting all
efforts to avoid a nuclear arms race with India and hoping for the
establishment of a strategic containing system in South Asia to
head off armed conflicts and maintain regional stability.
</P>
<P>
On Afghanistan, Sharif said Pakistan supports all efforts aimed
at realizing lasting peace in that country, noting that Pakistan
and Russia have had a series of consultations in the past few
months in a bid to carry on the peace process in Afghanistan.
</P>
