<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda: A Success Story in Anti-Drug Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has intensified its
efforts against drug smuggling and has proved a success story in
this aspect since 1996.
</P>
<P>
The country's Police Anti-Narcotics Unit has impounded one
million kilos of marijuana, 10,320 kilos of heroin and 1.8 kilos
of cocaine over this period, Tuesday's Monitor paper quoted the
latest report by the Interpol as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report said a total 266 people, including 22 foreigners
from Nigeria, Malawi, Rwanda, Tanzania and Kenya, have been
arrested while trying to smuggle marijuana out of the country.
Some 27 heroin smugglers and three cocaine traffickers have been
netted.
</P>
<P>
So far 150 have been charged and convicted while 81 cases are
pending, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The most common route used by drug traffickers from the Indian
sub- continent and Far East to Uganda has been Bombay-New Delhi
via Lahore-Tehran to the east Africa airports, a senior police
officer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report, however, indicated a marked increase in trafficking
through Kigali, Rwanda, to Uganda by road to avoid detection at
Entebbe International Airport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
