<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Loses $1 Million Per Week After Fish Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Uganda loses one million U.S.
dollars in foreign exchange earnings per week after the European
Union (EU) has tightened a knot on the temporary ban on fish
exports from east Africa.
</P>
<P>
Nsimbe Bulega, principal fisheries officer, made the revelation
Monday, according ot the Monitor daily.
</P>
<P>
He said the fisheries department had embarked on monitoring of
landing sites and submitted fish samples to government chemists as
one of the measures to evaluate methods to stem fish poisoning.
</P>
<P>
The EU has issued guidelines to east African countries before
lifting the ban. It demanded providing comprehensive information
on the control of sources of contamination.
</P>
<P>
They also asked for the details of quality control at the level
of individual fishing vessel to include guarantees concerning the
fishermen's knowledge of good hygiene practices. The conditions
were issued during a meeting held on April 14-15 in Brussels,
Belgium by 15 members of the European bloc and representatives
from the east African region.
</P>
<P>
The EU decided on April 12 to temporarily suspend importation
of fish from Kenya and Tanzania. The decision did not feature
Uganda because Uganda already imposed a ban on March 22.
</P>
<P>
Due to a fish ban imposed by the EU in December 1997, the value
of fish exports dropped by 11.6 percent from 34.6 million dollars
in 1996/1997 financial year to 31 million dollars in 1997/1998
because EU countries used to be the main importers of Uganda's
fish products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
