<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modest Growth Forecast for Namibia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Namibian economy is
projected to grow below three percent this year despite the
expected good growth in tourism and fishing.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Business Day newspaper Tuesday quoted the annual
report of the Bank of Namibia as saying that the growth would be
far below the average growth rate of five percent envisaged in the
First National Development Plan, and would be insufficient to
bring about an improvement in the per capita income of Namibians.
</P>
<P>
The paper did not say exactly when the annual report was
released.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the bank's governor, Tom Alweendo, as saying that
positive growth prospects for this year were expected to come from
the fishing and tourism industries as mining could remain weak
because of depressed international commodity markets.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is expected to benefit from the depreciation of the
Namibian dollar last year.
</P>
<P>
Fishing also seemed to have recovered fully and expectations
were that the sector's growth would surpass the robust rate of
last year. The projected growth rate of below three percent,
however, overturns a dismal one percent growth rate recorded last
year.
</P>
<P>
The projected economic growth would still be outstripped by the
country's population growth -- currently at about 3.2 percent a
year. This would mean gross domestic product per capita would keep
declining, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
