<HEADLINE> Mandela's Visit to Promote Ties: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese foreign ministry
spokesman expressed the conviction here today that South African
President Nelson Mandela's upcoming China visit will help push
forward the development of the overall bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, Sun Yuxi, president Mandela will
pay a state visit to China from May 5 to 7 at the invitation of
President Jiang Zemin, and they are expected to exchange views on
bilateral relations and issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
President Mandela will be the first South African president to
ever visit China.
</P>
<P>
Since China and South Africa established diplomatic relations
in 1998, bilateral ties have grown smoothly, the spokesman said.
According to him, Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao has exchanged
visits with his South African counterpart Thabo Mbeki; South
Africa has become China's largest trading partner in Africa; and
bilateral cooperation in the scientific, technological and
cultural sectors have also been expanded.
</P>
<P>
Sun noted that people of the two countries have maintained
traditional friendship, and China, along with the international
society, has always supported the South African people's struggle
against racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
President Mandela's visit will help further promote the
friendly relations between the two countries oriented to the next
century, he added. 
</P>
