<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Cotton Industry Facing Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Falling global commodity prices
and a slump in seed cotton yield for 1998/1999 season has put
zambia's cotton industry under severe pressure.
</P>
<P>
Seed cotton output for the current season has fallen by as much
as 25 percent to between 70,000 and 80,000 tons from the 105,000
tons of the previous season,Times of Zambia reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On the world market, the price of lint cotton has fallen by
31.25 percent in 12 months from 80 U.S. cents a pound, while the
excessive rains at the beginning of the season have affected
Zambia's cotton output.
</P>
<P>
Both Lonrho cotton managing director Nicky Wilkinson and Amaka
cotton ginneries general manager Titus Ikowa, representing some of
the leading players in the country's cotton industry, pointed to
the general slack in the world economy particularly in South East
Asia, which has dampened demand for the commodity.
</P>
<P>
Whereas farmers were offered 570 kwacha (about 24 U.S. cents)
per kilogram of seed cotton last year, the offer price this season
will depend on the development that will take place on the market.
</P>
<P>
Indications so far point to a price offer which is either equal
to last year's or slightly less.
</P>
<P>
Lonrho cotton has this season given out four million dollars in
pre- financing loans to farmers although the company is still owed
1.8 million dollars in credit by the farmers.
</P>
<P>
Wilkinson said it is unhealthy for his company to continue
carrying over the debt overhang from the farmers because it will
greatly reduce the company's ability to provide financing for the
production.
</P>
<P>
On the quality of Zambia's seed cotton, he said the country's
seed cotton is among the highest grade in terms of quality but
that the packaging of the product in polypropylene has affected
the lint and final textile products.
</P>
<P>
Lonrho cotton will introduce cotton picking bags made of cotton
and jute packing bags as a way of resolving the problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, "Lonrho cotton believes in the Zambian cotton
industry, we believe in long term profitability, and with the
land, the climate and the human resource the industry will win out
in the end if the fundamentals are right," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ikowa said there is no need for Zambian raw cotton to be
exported before it is processed and value added to it because the
country has the capacity to process the cotton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Expressway System Ranks Eighth Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua)-- China had put a 6,258-km
expressway system into operation by the end of last year, with the
length ranking eighth in the world, an official of the Ministry of
Communications said here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 12,600 km of expressways are still under construction,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
China initiated the construction of expressways in 1988 and
accelerated related projects during the 1990s. An average of 1,372
km of expressway was built annually in the past three years, with
1,487 km completed in 1998 alone.
</P>
<P>
China has used over 4.5 billion U.S. dollars provided by
international monetary organizations and foreign governments. A
large amount of funds was raised by various expressway companies
issuing H-shares in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
State funding and private investments have also accounted for a
substantial portion of related funds.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the length of the expressway systems
still falls short of demand. His ministry has plans for completing
two north-south and two east-east expressways by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
China will have five north-south and seven east-west
expressways by 2010, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
