<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Orders More Money for Loan to Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has ordered the release of an additional 200 million pesos
(5 million U.S. dollars) for an emergency loan facility to workers
who lost their jobs or suffered income cuts as a result of the
currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Philippines' Social Security System (SSS)
Carlos Arellano said Tuesday that borrowers must present a
certification from their employers attesting that they suffered
lower pay not earlier than July 7, 1997 as a result of job
rotation or reduced work hours.
</P>
<P>
The additional funding brings to 500 million pesos (12.5
million dollars) the total amount intended for emergency loans to
workers. The 300 million pesos (7.5 million dollars) already
allocated for the program after it was launched in April last
year, has been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
Arellano said the loan facility will be open to active SSS
members who were affected by the crisis, including overseas
Filipino members.
</P>
<P>
The SSS will process a maximum loan of 12,500 pesos (312.5
dollars) at a 6-percent interest rate per annum and payable in two
years after a 12-month moratorium until the 200 million (5 million
dollars) is exhausted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
