<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian FM to Meet Israeli Prime Ministerial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov is to arrive in Israel on Thursday in a gesture to despel
talks that Russia favors incumbent Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu in the May 17 elections.
</P>
<P>
According to the Israeli Foreign Ministry, Ivanov is slated to
meet with three prime ministerial candidates Ehud Barak of the
Labor party, and Yitzhak Mordechai of the center party and
Netanyahu of the Likud bloc.
</P>
<P>
The meetings were arranged at the request of the Russian side,
which is seeking to counter the impression that Russia has been
intervening in Israel's election campaign in an effort to promote
Netanyahu's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
When Netanyahu visited Moscow last month, Russian Prime
Minister Yevgevy Primakov was widely reported to have said if
he were an Israeli citizen, he would vote for Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
After hearing those remarks of Primakov, Barak, Mordechai and
leaders of other political parties launched their attacks against
Netanyahu, saying Netanyahu's Russian visit was nothing but an
election campaign in Moscow to drum up support of over 600,000
Russian immigrants in Israel.
</P>
<P>
While in Israel, Ivanov is also set to hold meetings with
President Ezer Weizman, Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon and
Minister of Industry and Trade Natan Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials are expected to raise the issue of
Russia's sales of military technology and equipment to Iran, as
well as Russia's reported plan to sell anti-tank weaponry to
Syria.
</P>
<P>
The issue of promoting strategic cooperation between Israel and
Russia will also be on the agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
