<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France: Legal Basis Needed for Oil Embargo on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- France said on Tuesday that a solid
legal basis is needed to impose an oil embargo on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
France expressed doubt about the U.S. call for oil embargo
which it said could turn the Adriatic Sea into a second Persian
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
"There is no disagreement about the objective (of blocking
Yugoslavia's oil import), but we need a solid legal basis which
does not exist," said French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine in an
interview with the daily newspaper Le Figaro.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia imports oil from tankers calling at the coast of
Montenegro and through oil pipelines running through its
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. daily New York Times said that Washington has proposed
imposing an oil embargo on Yugoslavia by banning oil shipments by
the sea.
</P>
<P>
"The objective is logic. But we need a solid legal basis. But
it does not exist. We need to think about it more," said Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
American officials said that it is ridiculous to risk the lives
of NATO pilots bombing oil storage centers and refineries in
Yugoslavia, while Belgrade continues to obtain oil supplies from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials made the proposal at a NATO ambassadors' meeting
last week in Brussels, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said that the Americans made the proposal in "a
somewhat rash way" because the proposal has not been subjected to
enough study.
</P>
<P>
"To transform the Adriatic Sea into a Persian Gulf is not
necessarily a good idea," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
