<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Race Gap Slowly Narrowing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Reality Check researchers, who made a survey of 3,000 house-the
holds countrywide, looked at eight criteria: formal housing; an
inside toilet; inside water; rubbish removal; more than basic
education; enough food; above minimum income; and employment.
</P>
<P>
Most people surveyed live in formal brick homes, nine percent
in shacks, and around three in 10 in rural farm homes or huts.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the homes had an inside flush toilet. Inside tap
water is enjoyed by almost all whites and Indians and one third of
black people.
</P>
<P>
Seven in 10 black family use electricity. More than nine in 10
whites, Indians and coloreds have their rubbish removed at least
weekly against 55 percent of black house-holds.
</P>
<P>
Only two percent of whites, three percent of Indians and 11
percent of coloreds, against one third of Black people, go hungry
a few times a month.
</P>
<P>
Education has steadily improved. Almost all African children
are now receiving some education.
</P>
<P>
One in three people surveyed have a full-time job, while a
quarter are jobless.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that income levels were difficult to pinpoint
since many people refused to reveal this information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
