<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading British Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading British newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Times:
</P>
<P>
-- NATO is using intelligence supplied by the Kosovo Liberation
Army on the ground to help its planes to locate and destroy Serb
positions in the war-torn province.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph:
</P>
<P>
-- After five days of denials, confusion, claim and counter-
claim, NATO admitted Monday that its aircraft bombed two refugee
convoys in Kosovo last week.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian:
</P>
<P>
-- NATO's "mistaken" bombing of a refugee convoy last Wednesday
has led to a surge in skepticism with a significant minority of
British voters "thinking again" about their support for the air
raids on Yugoslavia, according to the Guardian/ICM opinion poll
published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Independent:
</P>
<P>
-- Labor Party leader Tony Blair, now prime minister, had told
Liberal Democratic Party leader Paddy Ashdown on polling day in
1997 that he would form a coalition government with the Liberal
Democrats even if he won a bigger than expected majority.
</P>
<P>
Financial Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Serious difficulties emerged last night within Telecom
Italia over the company's proposed merger with Deutsche Telekom,
forcing the Italian company's board to adjourn a meeting called to
approve the deal to create a European tele-communications giant.
</P>
</TEXT>
