<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican FM for Regional Conflict Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Minister of Foreign
Affairs and Cooperation Leonardo Simao has called for the setting
up of regional conflict resolution mechanism as an effective
functional agency of the Southern African Development COmmunity
(SADC).
</P>
<P>
Simao made the call Monday during a speech at parliament, the
Noticias newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are making efforts in safeguarding regional peace through
joint exercises and changes of experience among regional
partners," he said.
</P>
<P>
After recalling the Mozambique's participation of liberation
struggle in Zimbabwe and South Africa, Simao said the challenges
now facing southern Africa are regional stability, economic growth
and development.
</P>
<P>
The African continent is getting more and more marginalized in
the globalization process due to the unstable factors in the Great
Lakes region and Angola, in Zimbabwe, Swaziland and Lesotho, as
well as constant border conflicts, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the foreign minister, his government believed that
peace does not necessarily mean without war. The instability in
Mozambique's neighbors mean lack of security in the country
itself, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has been working for regional stability through
diplomatic and security channels such as enhancing cooperation and
coordination to prevent and eliminate crisis.
</P>
<P>
Simao revealed that his country will take actions against
crimes to ensure stability in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The sub-region is rich in natural resources, with 90 percent of
the world's platinum, 85 percent of chromium, 75 percent of
manganese and 50 percent of gold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
