<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Border Trade on Increase in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The total value of imports and
exports in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province for the first
quarter this year has reached 243.13 million U.S. dollars, up 7.5
percent from the corresponding 1998 period.
</P>
<P>
The import value for the first quarter was 103.57 million U.S.
dollars, 30.9 percent more than last year, and exports were 95.1
million, a slight increase over the same period of last year. So
far, 148 enterprises in the province have engaged in import and
export business, 12 more than in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that imports have focused on timber, paper pulp,
steel, and chemical materials, occupying 83.2 percent of the total,
and timber import value was 29.39 million U.S. dollars, 28.4
percent of the total. The main exports have been clothing, light
industrial products, food, and textiles, with textiles accounting
for 34.3 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Ji Qingfu, an official with the Heilongjiang Provincial Border
Trade Administrative Bureau, said there are two reasons for the
increase. One, greater competitiveness has inspired the vitality
of the enterprises; two, enterprises initiated some timely changes
to suit the changing market. For example, the state's forest-
protection policy has accelerated imports of timber and paper pulp
from Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
