<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 09:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Occupation of Lebanese Village Disrupts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Israel's occupation last week
of a village in south Lebanon has forced the U.S. to cut short a
mediation effort aimed at having a Lebanese gendarmerie unit
deployed in the village, a local daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. holds that the fencing off of the village of Arnoun by
Israeli army was a surprise and disrupted an effort that had been
supported by the Lebanese government, the Haaretz daily said.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed that Hezbollah guerrillas were using Arnoun as
a launching pad for attacks on its military outposts in the
so-called security zone in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had suggested that Beirut send government troops into
the village, which sits just outside the buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government had first denied the initiative, made
at Israel's behest, for fear that the deployment of such forces
would be interpreted as an action directed against Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
But it eventually agreed to station gendarmes in the village
since the gendarmerie is a police unit and will be perceived to be
upholding Lebanese law and sovereignty, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Washington's mediation effort, however, was terminated after
Israeli soldiers entered Arnoun and set up barbed wire around it
last Friday, several days after an Israeli soldier was killed by
a roadside bomb near the village.
</P>
<P>
Arnoun came under spotlight in mid-February when the Israeli
army fenced off this mostly-deserted village to include it into
the security zone, claiming that Hezbollah guerrillas had used it
as bases in violation of a ceasefire understanding reached in
1996.
</P>
<P>
But with the support of the Lebanese government, angry student
protesters tore down the fence a few days later.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the 15-kilometer-deep "security zone" in south
Lebanon in 1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its northern
border areas.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, has since been the most active
guerrilla groups fighting to end the Israeli occupation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
