<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Decline Moderates in Singapore's External Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The long-unabated decline in
Singapore's external trade moderated in March with the total trade
falling by 9.4 percent year-on-year after five consecutive months
of two-digit contraction, according to data released Tuesday by
Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB).
</P>
<P>
Non-oil domestic export (NODX) declined 3.2 percent, an
improvement over the more severe declines of 6.0 percent and 5.9
percent in January and February respectively. There were signs of
improvement in the domestic export of electronic products which
shrank by a more moderate rate of 4.7 percent in the month.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil imports contracted by 9.3 percent in March, a more
moderate figure than the double-digit declines in the proceeding
months.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, non-oil re-exports (NORX) remained weak, shrinking
by 15.4 percent during the month.
</P>
<P>
Domestic exports of oil fell by 7.9 percent in March, less
severe as compared to the 12.3 percent contraction in the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
Of the top markets for NODX, the EU market remained buoyant
with a growth of 6.4 percent, the U.S. market declined by 6.8
percent due in part to overall weakness in U.S. imports of
electronics (which accounts for 87 percent of Singapore's NODX to
the market) and the Malaysia market sank by 7.1 percent compared
to the more severe contraction of 10 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Japan market was marginally down 0.9 percent,
a sign of improvement compared with the two-digit declines in the
past 10 consecutive months, and the Hong Kong market plunged by
21.4 percent, the 11th consecutive month of decline.
</P>
<P>
However, NODX to the emerging markets deteriorated in March,
falling by 8.8 percent. But the China market is an exception which
expanded by 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Summing up the performance in March, the TDB said the
deterioration of Singapore's external trade experienced in the
preceding 10 months appeared to be stabilizing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
