<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Communist Leader Remains Unconscious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Man Mohan Adhikari, chairman of
the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML),
remained unconscious Tuesday following a heart attack on Monday,
the Teaching Hospital said in a bulletin.
</P>
<P>
However, his general conditions were stable, the bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
A party source said the 79-year-old leader was in "serious and
critical conditions." "We're not hoping he will get better," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said a CT scan found that Adhikari's heart, lung and brain
are disconnected.
</P>
<P>
He said the doctors were doing their best and three or four
doctors from India are arriving.
</P>
<P>
Adhikari fainted Monday when he was returning from an election
campaign in the capital. He was his party's prime ministerial
candidate for the election to the House of Representatives on May
3 and May 17.
</P>
<P>
When he was sent to the hospital, he had no pulse and
heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
He became the kingdom's first communist prime minister after
his party secured the largest number of votes in the mid-term
polls in November 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
