<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Announces Further Measures to Spur Domestic Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- China today announced new
measures to stimulate domestic demand in order to reach the
projected 7 percent economic growth target for 1999.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here, Zheng Xinli, spokesman for the
State Development and Planning Commission (SDPC), said the
government will increase investment in agricultural infrastructure
by an additional 30 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Investment in transportation, telecommunications, rural
electricity networks, state grain warehouses, and urban
infrastructure will also be increased by 25 billion yuan, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The government has pledged to adjust its policies regarding
bank loans, investment regulations, and market access to encourage
enterprises with all types of ownership to invest in the economy.
</P>
<P>
To spur the market for consumer products, the government said
it will improve the incomes of disadvantaged urban residents and
farmers. A salary increase is also being considered for civil
servants.
</P>
<P>
The government announced policy adjustments to encourage
consumption, including accelerated housing reform, expansion of
credit, and the development of tourism and community services.
</P>
<P>
To stimulate the rural market, the government pledged further
efforts to improve power and water supplies and road networks in
rural areas. The development of small towns will also be
encouraged.
</P>
<P>
To expand exports, the government will accelerate the reform of
foreign trade policies, including relaxing restrictions on exports
by non-state-owned firms and a continued crackdown on smuggling,
the SDPC said. 
</P>
