<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Rate in New Zealand Hits New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand has, for the first
time since 1946, reported a negative annual inflation, a
government statistician said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a media release, government statistician Len Cook said the
consumers price index (CPI), which measures inflation, fell 0.1
percent in the fiscal year ending March 1999.
</P>
<P>
On a quarterly basis, prices in New Zealand fell 0.3 percent in
the first quarter of this year, after dropping 0.8 percent in the
previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
Prices fell in the year to March, giving New Zealand one of the
 lowest inflation rates in the world.
</P>
<P>
Local economists say that tumbling interest rates in the
country have driven the fall. Late last year mortgage rates in New
Zealand fell to 30-year lows and interest rates are now 19 percent
lower than they were a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
