<HEADLINE> Qinghai Cracks Down on Tibetan Antelope Poaching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Rangers at Qinghai Province's Hoh
Xil Nature Reserve have charged more than 10 people with poaching
Tibetan antelope and confiscated 540 furs since January.
</P>
<P>
The reserve, located on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, is home to
more than 20 rare species under State protection, including Yak
and Tibetan antelope.
</P>
<P>
The aforementioned suspects allegedly poached Tibetan antelope
in order to profit from smuggling furs.
</P>
<P>
The reserve's administrative bureau established a center in
January as part of an effort to crack down on the increasing
number poaching and smuggling cases involving Tibetan antelope,
according to one bureau official.
</P>
<P>
Center staffers arrested eight suspects and seized 332 furs in
the first two months of the year, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Rangers cracked an armed gang and confiscated two rifles, 1,300
rounds of ammunition and two jeeps in March this year.
</P>
<P>
The official called for financial support from domestic and
overseas organizations to overcome the reserve's lack of funds and
equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
