<HEADLINE> Agreement to Resolve DRC Crisis Signed in Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A regional summit held in Libya
on the situation in the democratic republic of congo (drc) has
ended with a communique calling for an immediate cease-fire to
pave way for peaceful resolution to the eight-month conflict
there.
</P>
<P>
the summit , which started in libya's northern town of sirte
saturday, was chaired by libyan leader muammar gaddafi and was
attended by ugandan president yoweri museveni, drc president
laurent kabila, eritrean president issaias afewerki and chadian
president idriss debie, a press release from the ugandan
president's office said here monday.
</P>
<P>
in a joint communique signed by the regional leaders, they
stressed the need for security and integrity of the borders of all
the states concerned and agreed on the deployment of a neutral
african peace-keeping force in areas now under control of foreign
troops in the drc.
</P>
<P>
the summit condemned all acts of violence and mass murder and
affirmed the need to pursue the murderers and punish them.
</P>
<P>
on a peaceful settlement of the issue, the leaders agreed that
drc government should encourage and pursue a policy of national
dialog involving all parties concerned in the drc.
</P>
<P>
they held that as soon as a peaceful agreement is reached, all
foreign forces in the drc should be withdrawn. they called for a
commitment to respecting the principle of non-interference in the
internal affairs of countries.
</P>
<P>
the war in the drc erupted in early august last year. kabila's
government has military support from zimbabwe, namibia, angola and
chad while the tutsi rebels fighting to oust kabila are allegedly
backed by uganda and rwanda.
</P>
<P>
the war has never ceased in spite of regional and international
efforts to bring the armed conflict to an end.
</P>
<P>
the prolonged war has exerted a heavy economic burden on all
the key players involved in the war. enditem

NNNN
14:52 14:53 g # PAB
</P>
