<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP Chief Commends Report on Forests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, AAApril 20 (Xinhua) -- Executive director of the
United Nations Environment Program (UNEP), Klaus Toepfer, Monday
praised a report of the world commission on forests and
sustainable development for mapping out a blueprint to solve the
global forest crisis.
</P>
<P>
The report entitled "our forests... our future" was released
monday in washington, the united states.
</P>
<P>
"the report offers a way out of the forest crisis because it
specifies reforms needed from abandoning subsidies and tax
incentives that provoke forest destruction to more openness in
timber allocation procedures and landscape planning," toepfer said
in nairobi, kenya's capital.
</P>
<P>
toepfer, who is also a member of the commission on forests,
noted the loss of millions of hectares of forest annually is
serious because of the ecological services forests provide in
terms of the hydrological cycle, soil conservation, biological
diversity and weather patterns.
</P>
<P>
after holding hearings on five continents, the commission on
forests released the report, saying that by changing the way
people manage forests, both development and forests can be
sustained.
</P>
<P>
through the public hearings the commission has organized, the
report gives a warning to people who live in the forests, who make
a living from the forests, and to other people who have a stake in
the future of the forests.
</P>
<P>
according to the report, from siberia to haiti, the world's
forests are exploited far beyond their ability to reproduce.
</P>
<P>
nearly 75 percent of the tropical forests in west africa have
been lost since 1950. thailand lost a third of its forests in the
1980's.
</P>
<P>
forests face an even shakier future with the global population
expected to grow by 50 percent in the first half of next century,
the report added. enditem

NNNN
14:57 14:57 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
