<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Details Added China Opens First Asset Management Company (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- China's first asset management
company focusing on non-performing bank loans officially opened
today in the Chinese capital with State Council approval.
</P>
<P>
The long-awaited Cinda Asset Management Corporation, with
registered capital of 10 billion yuan, will mainly deals with the
management of non-performing loans and assets transferred from
banks.
</P>
<P>
Cinda is an independent state-owned financial institution under
the supervision of the People's Bank of China (PBOC), China's
central bank. The company will also handle trust-related
transactions for the PBOC and various other financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Cinda President Zhu Dengshan said that the State Council's
decision to strip the China Construction Bank (CCB) of non-
performing loans and place same under the company's professional
management is based on objective judgment of the nation's current
economic and financial conditions, and international experience.
</P>
<P>
"The move demonstrates the government's clear understanding of
and resolve to solve existing problems," according to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
PBOC Deputy-Governor Yan Haiwang pointed out that state-owned
commercial banks have played a significant role in financing
production and construction, and providing effective support for
national economic development.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that commercial banks have accumulated a
relatively high volume of non-performing loans due to various
problems related to domestic economic and financial operation, as
well as the impact of the regional financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The aforementioned factors may threaten the healthy and stable
development of China's financial system and adversely affect the
national economy, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Details Added China Opens First Asset Management Company (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The establishment of Cinda is an important step in China's
financial system reform. Cinda will be a significant driving force
for preventing and minimizing financial risks, improving the
quality of credit assets and promoting further reform of state-
owned enterprises," Yan said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Ministry of Finance will allocate some 10
billion yuan in capital as the registered capital of Cinda and the
State Council will appoint and remove the company's president and
vice-presidents.
</P>
<P>
A supervisory committee has also been established to oversee
Cinda's management and operational decisions.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Dengshan said that Cinda will purchase non-performing loans
from the CCB in the near future.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Cinda's major business activities will involve
purchasing and performing trust management for non-performing
loans accumulated by commercial banks; debt retrieval and
restructuring; investment consulting; borrowing from financial
institutions and applying to the central bank for re-lending fund;
issuing bonds; direct investments; and various activities
involving other sectors.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has ratified Cinda's exemption from taxation
in the process of purchasing, assuming and handling non-performing
loans.
</P>
<P>
CCB President Zhou Xiaochuan said the CCB is actively clearing
credit assets in preparation for transferring non-performing loans
to Cinda.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the establishment of Cinda will help promote the
bank's internal management system reform.  
</P>
</TEXT>
