<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Maintains Ban on E. African Fish Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Union will
maintain the ban on importing fish from Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda
although representatives from the three countries have tried to
persuade EU to lift it.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the three Lake Victoria countries held a
two-day technical meeting with EU in Brussels, Belgium last week,
trying to break the deadlock but in vain, The Guardian newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On March 30, EU announced a total ban on fresh and frozen fish
imports from the three east African countries following reports
that unscrupulous fishermen have been using chemical substances to
poison fish in Lake Victoria, the world's second largest fresh
water lake, posing threats to people's health.
</P>
<P>
The ban deals a heavy blow to the countries as Tanzania earns
85.6 million U.S. dollars annually from the fish industry along
the lake, providing 4,000 jobs, while Uganda earns some 70 million
U.S. dollars and Kenya earns some 91 million from the sector.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has claimed that the lake area on its side is poison
free as security forces have stepped up patrols. Uganda and Kenya
have also strengthened attacks on fish poisoning.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, EU has given conditions to the three
countries to fulfill before the ban could be lifted, sources said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 07:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Team Wins Environment Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 20 (Xinhua) - An Israeli and Palestinian
environmental team has received an international award from the
Time magazine for its work saving the lesser kestrel in Jerusalem
and the West Bank town of Jerico, a local daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Professor Dan Alon from Israel and Professor Nader Hattib
from Bethlehem are among the recipients of Time's annual "Heroes
of the Planet", The Jerusalem Post said.
</P>
<P>
The award is given annually to people who have contributed
to protecting the earth from ecological dangers.
</P>
<P>
Alon and Hattib are responsible for a project aimed at saving
the lesser kestrels by, among other things, constructing nesting
boxes for them around Jerusalem and Jericho.
</P>
<P>
The lesser kestrel, a bird of prey, is under serious threat of
extinction worldwide. The number of lesser kestrels nested in the
Jerusalem and Jericho areas have decreased in the last several
years due to rapid growth of buildings.
</P>
<P>
Alon said he hoped the award will help promote cooperation in
environmental and conservation areas in the entire Middle East,
according to the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
