<HEADLINE> Russian Patriarch Travels to Yugoslavia on Peace Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A Russian Orthodox delegation
headed by Patriarch Alexy II left here Tuesday for Belgrade on a
one-day mission to seek peaceful solutions to the current
conflicts in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving, Alexy II told ITAR-TASS news agency that the
major purposes of this mission are to urge NATO to stop its
military actions against Yugoslavia and to create conditions for
negotiations on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
The principle condition for negotiations to start was an end to
NATO air raids on Yugoslavia and all military operations on the
ground, said Alexy II.
</P>
<P>
"Only a peaceful and dignified life for all, including the
Kosovo Albanians, can maintain the entity of the country and
foster order and good understanding," he added.
</P>
<P>
Besides meeting with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in
Belgrade, Alexy II is also expected to pray for the people dead in
the conflicts. 
</P>
