<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT: Murderer of HK Residents Executed in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Li Yuhui, who poisoned to death
five Hong Kong residents last year, was executed today in the city
of Shantou, south China's Guangdong Province, after the provincial
Higher People's Court rejected Li's appeal and upheld the original
death sentence verdict.
</P>
<P>
A native of Shantou, Li murdered five residents of Hong Kong on
July 21, 1998, at a so-called religious ceremony designed to
prolong their life as he claimed, and then slipped back to the
inland area with 1.2 million Hong Kong dollars which he took from
his victims.
</P>
<P>
Li, 47, was charged with killing the five Hong Kong residents
by offering them some so-called magic water, which was in fact a
mixture of mineral water and potassium cyanide that Li himself
prepared.
</P>
<P>
On March 23, this year, the Intermediate People's Court in
Shantou put Li on public trial. Convicted of intentional homicide
and robbery, Li was given the death sentence and deprived of his
political rights for life and all of his possessions.
</P>
<P>
Li then appealed to the Guangdong Provincial Higher People's
Court, but was rejected when the court confirmed that the original
ruling was accurate and fair, and should be maintained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
