<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Projects Positive Growth for Malaysia in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) has projected a positive growth of 0.7 percent for Malaysia
this year and 2.7 percent in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia itself officially forecast a 1-percent growth this
year against a contraction of 6.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the Malaysian national news agency Bernama
Tuesday, ADB said in its report on the Asian Development Outlook
1999 released in Washington Monday that Malaysia's prospects for
recovery in the medium term depend on the government taking
credible action to reform the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The revival of investor confidence, which is the key to
sustainable growth, critically hinges on the speedy resolution of
the banking system's non-performing loan problem and of corporate
debt issues in an objective and transparent manner, ADB said.
</P>
<P>
According to ADB, expansionary monetary and fiscal policies in
Malaysia are expected to boost aggregate demand moderately in
1999.
</P>
<P>
Forecasts suggest that private consumption will grow by 0.8
percent while public consumption will grow marginally, private
investment will grow by 0.6 percent, public investment 2.2 percent
and exports of goods 3.8 percent in 1999, because of the likely
slow growth of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
The ADB report said that given the slight overall growth in the
domestic economy, imports are projected to rise by 6.6 percent,
leaving the current account in surplus.
</P>
<P>
Describing the forecast on Malaysia as "somewhat optimistic,"
the report said the projections assume the availability of
adequate domestic and external funds for financing the public
sector's borrowing requirements and covering the costs of bank
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
It said enhancing the productivity of human resources is a key
challenge for Malaysia's international competitiveness and
long-term development.
</P>
<P>
Increasing the skills of its labor force will enable Malaysia
to export more high-technology goods, thus increasing its export
competitiveness and enabling it to compete more effectively in the
global market, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
