<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil, Colombia to Build Big Steel Complex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Brazil and Colombia signed a
letter of intent here Monday on building a steel complex, which
will be the largest in the Caribbean region.
</P>
<P>
The project will be constructed in the Colombian coast city of
Puerto Bolivar, with a joint investment of 600 million U.S.
dollars from 12 Brazilian and six Colombian companies.
</P>
<P>
The venture has a designed annual capacity of one million tons
of steel reels utilizing Brazil's iron and Colombia's coal. The
products will be exported mainly to the Southern Common Market (
Mercosur) and North America.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed by Brazilian Vice President Marco
Marciel and his visiting Colombian counterpart Gustavo Bell Lemus,
who is on a four-day visit since Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
