<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of the Macao SAR Basic Law (42) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 42 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
What will be the nature of the municipal organizations of the
MSAR?
</P>
<P>
Municipal organizations have long existed in Macao. They used
to be called municipal assemblies of Macao and were later called
city halls.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are two city halls: Macao City Hall and
Islands City Hall. The city halls enjoy autonomy in both
administrative and financial affairs and are each composed of a
municipal assembly and a municipal executive council.
</P>
<P>
The municipal assembly is a policy-making body and its members
are elected directly and indirectly or appointed by the Governor,
while the municipal executive council is an executive organ and
its members are appointed by the Governor or elected by, and from
among, the members of the municipal assembly.
</P>
<P>
The city halls have the following main responsibilities and
duties:
</P>
<P>
-- Conduct city planning and make proposals in this regard;
</P>
<P>
-- Take charge of municipal works, public health and hygiene,
culture, sports and recreational facilities so as to maintain and
ensure a sound living environment for their residents; and
</P>
<P>
-- Issue licenses for vehicles and vendors in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Article 95 of the Basic Law stipulates that, in the light of
the actual conditions in Macao, the MSAR may set up non-policy-
making municipal organizations.
</P>
<P>
Entrusted by the government of the Region, such municipal
organizations shall provide services in such fields as culture,
recreation and environmental sanitation, and shall be consulted by
the government of the Region on the above-mentioned affairs.
</P>
<P>
This article of the Basic Law shows due respect for the system
of the municipal organizations of Macao and its development.
</P>
<P>
Retaining these organizations will help maintain social
stability and achieve a smooth transition. At the same time, it
also shows that it is not necessary to set up a two-tier organ of
power in a small place like Macao with a dense population.
</P>
<P>
Giving the municipal organizations of the MSAR non-political
power status will facilitate both their provision of services to
local residents and ensure unified leadership and management of
the Government of the MSAR.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Constructs 400 Pilot Urban Residential Quarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of
Construction has built around 400 pilot residential quarters in
urban areas throughout the country in a bid to improve the quality
of life and provide models for the country's home builders.
</P>
<P>
According to Gao Zheng, an official in charge of the
construction of the experimental residential quarters, the
ministry has set high standards for building materials, design,
landscaping and other auxiliary facilities in the building of
these pilot residences, and every completed project should be 100-
percent certified, he said
</P>
<P>
He said that China is in the midst of massive housing
construction, building homes with a total of 300 million square
meters of floor space last year. To realize the goal of increasing
the per capita living space of urban residents to nine square
meters, the country needs to complete the building of apartments
with a total floor space of 240 million square meters every year.
</P>
<P>
"Speaking from an overall point of view, the quality of China's
housing construction is not high, and there also exists many
quality problems common in housing construction," said the
official, who stressed the necessity of building more experimental
residential apartments in different areas as a reference for all
builders.
</P>
<P>
The campaign to build experimental residential quarters was
first launched in 1986, and the program has helped improve the
overall quality of apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
Provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions are urged to
build at least 25 percent of their apartments according to the
standards set for experimental residential quarters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
