<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Government Approves Agriculture Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
approved the country's first National Agriculture Policy which is
aimed at boosting food production and achieving self-sufficiency
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the policy, which was approved on Monday,
is to make the nation self-reliant in food through boosting
production of all crops, The Daily Star newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The policy stresses the need for optimum utilization of the
country's limited cultivable land, a cabinet member was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Besides, it has proposed a lot of mechanism to strengthen the
private sector in agriculture. At the same time, it has underlined
the need for constant monitoring by the state that the fertility
of land is not affected due to use of bad fertilizer or seeds," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture policy proposes a provision for setting up an
Agricultural Loan Foundation to look after disbursement of
agricultural loans among certain categories of farmers.
</P>
<P>
And agricultural loan committees would be set up at different
levels, which would have a say in the process of disbursement of
agricultural loans among farmers, according to the policy, which
was placed before the cabinet in November last year.
</P>
<P>
The policy also keeps a prevision for inclusion of farmers'
representatives in the National Agriculture Committee, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, with an agriculture-based economy, has an annual
food shortage of about 2 million tons, and about 80 percent of its
126-million population live in rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
