<HEADLINE> DPRK Denies Accepting U.S."Peace Force" in S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The stance of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea on the withdrawal of U.S. troops from
South Korea has remained unchanged, said a leading Pyongyang
newspaper Rodong Sinmun on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. troops in South Korea serve as the commando for
aggression against the DPRK and offer the fundamental obstacle to
the unification of the Korean Peninsula, said a commentary in the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK would on no account change its stand. So long as the
U.S. maintains its military presence in South Korea, lasting peace
and reunification of the Korean Peninsula would be beyond
imagination, the article added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. side has recently claimed, through South Korean
mouthpieces, that the DPRK would acknowledge the American military
presence if the South Korea-based U.S. troops stay on as "a peace
force."
</P>
<P>
South Korea echoed the claim by saying that the fifth round of
the four-party talks would not include American military presence
in its formal agenda, said the article.
</P>
<P>
The commentary reiterated that American troop withdrawal is the
basic topic for the talks. Without discussing the military pullout,
the talks will lose its significance, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
