<HEADLINE> Malaysia Launches National Anti-Mosquito Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Tuesday launched a
national cleanliness and anti-mosquito campaign to bring about a
higher and sustained level of public consciousness about
cleanliness.
</P>
<P>
The campaign aims to intensify efforts to remove public apathy
toward maintaining cleanliness and destroying mosquito-breeding
grounds within human settlements.
</P>
<P>
Launching the campaign here, Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah
Ahmad Badawi called for greater efforts on a sustained basis to
deal with mosquito-related problems.
</P>
<P>
He said that as for the government it would mobilize its entire
machinery in the campaign and as for the community,
non-governmental organizations and the private sector, they would
be involved in setting up action groups to carry out cleaning up
work and ensure strict enforcement of legislation relating to
cleanliness.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that without public participation, combating the
mosquito menace would not achieve the desired results even with
the entire government machinery mobilized.
</P>
<P>
He also called for continuous research into behavioral links
between mosquitoes and humans.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was launched in the wake of the recent outbreak of
the Japanese Encephalitis (JE) and Nipah virus in pig farming
areas in the country, said to be passed from infected pigs to
humans by the Culex mosquito.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia destroyed some 650,000 pigs in the southern state of
Negeri Sembilan, most seriously affected by JE and the Nipah
virus, in the past month.
</P>
<P>
The deadly disease passed by mosquitoes from infected pigs to
humans has claimed dozens of lives in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
