<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Governor's Remarks on Nanjing Massacre Refuted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Newly-elected Tokyo Governor
Shintaro Ishihara's recent denial of the Rape of Nanjing committed
by Japanese militarists during World War Two has been bitterly
refuted by a leading Chinese historian as "ultra-nationalist."
</P>
<P>
Professor Gao Xingzu of the History Department of Nanjing
University said in a signed article published in Nanjing-based
Xinhua Daily on Sunday that Ishihara's remarks made in a
television interview on April 12 were meant to bring about a fresh
wave of anti-China campaign.
</P>
<P>
Gao, also chairman of a research society exclusive on the
Nanjing massacre, pointed out in the article that the historical
event was "not only the most representative and typical in the
crimes committed by the Japanese aggressors in China, but also the
most barbarian and the darkest ever chapter in human history."
</P>
<P>
During the six weeks after Japanese aggressors occupied Nanjing
on December 13, 1937, 300,000 Chinese civilians and disarmed
soldiers were slaughtered, together with countless cases of raping,
looting and arsons, and one third of the city burned down to the
ground. The incidents were judged to be a war crime by the post-
war Far Eastern international military tribunal.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, Ishihara, a representative veteran ultra-
rightist in Japan, said the Nanjing massacre was a "fabrication"
made by the Chinese. In the just-ended gubernatorial election, he
again defended Japan's crimes of aggression. "His nonsense will
only stir great indignation on the part of the Chinese people,"
the article said.
</P>
<P>
"Ishihara's denial of the war crimes is not in any way linked
with his ignorance of history... but based on his stubborn
adherence to ultra-nationalism," Gao said.
</P>
<P>
Ishihara's ultra-nationalism can be better illustrated by his
book published 10 years ago entitled "A Japan that Dares to Say No,
" which claimed that "it is the right time for Japan to get rid of
its character of slavery," urging a greater role for Japan in the
world arena, especially Asia, Gao noted.
</P>
<P>
These remarks, Gao pointed out, echoed the Japanese fascists'
vowed ambition to be "Asia's leader" in the early 1920's, which
led to a series of disastrous war by Japanese militarists against
Asian countries including China.
</P>
<P>
Ishihara's remarks came at a time when Japan, during high-level
official talks and a China-Japan joint communique issued last year,
acknowledged its aggression against China, pledged in-depth review
of and apologized for the enormous disaster inflicted on China
during the aggression.
</P>
<P>
"Never will we allow a resurgence of the militarist trend and
force in any form," the professor said, noting that a handful of
Japanese political rightists have always cast shadow over the Sino-
Japanese friendly relationship, which has seen an all-round
development since the normalization of official relations in 1972.
</P>
<P>
"We would advise Mr. Ishihara that he had better be sober
rather than be a wheeler-dealer running against the historical
trend," the article concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
