<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Jobless People Estimated at 6.37 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The number of unemployed persons
in Indonesia this year will increase by 30 percent to 6.37
million, the Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS) predicted.
</P>
<P>
This assumption is closely related to the condition in 1998 in
which it was difficult and took a long time for unemployed persons
to find jobs, BPS' manpower researcher Hananto said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the number of unemployed persons in Indonesia was
5.06 million, Antara News Agency Tuesday quoted Hananto as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of veteran workers is expected to increase
to 4.5 million and job seekers not absorbed in the labor sector
would be 30 percent, or 1.35 million.
</P>
<P>
The rising number of newcomers estimated at 3.5 million as a
result of a high number of school dropouts will most likely raise
the number of unemployed persons in 1999, he added.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Indonesia's labor force was 89.6 million and increased
to 92.73 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's labor force in 1999 is expected to reach
95 million to 96 million.
</P>
<P>
The economic crisis has raised the country's unemployment rate,
and most of the people who lost jobs as a result of the crisis are
employed in the informal sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the economic crisis, the agricultural sector has become
the primary sector in which the number of workers increased to 11
percent from 8 percent for urban areas and to 63 percent from 58
percent for rural areas.
</P>
<P>
He also noted a drop in the number of workers employed in the
industrial, electrical, gas, financial and banking sectors.
</P>
<P>
The number of job openings in these sectors drops to 23 percent
from 26 percent for urban areas, and to 13 percent from 15 percent
for rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The economic crisis has also reduced workers' income by up to
28 percent for rural areas and 24 percent for urban areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
