<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Opposition NAP Chief Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's opposition New
Aspiration Party (NAP) leader Chavalit Yongchaiyudh has tendered
his resignation from the party leadership in a surprise move to
effect changes in the party line-up.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit, a former prime minister, took the move after an NAP
executive committee meeting on Monday. He said in a statement
available on Tuesday that his resignation should lead to changes
in accordance with the aspirations of party members, the people
and the calls from the mass media.
</P>
<P>
He said the upcoming changes would boost the party's
effectiveness in serving the people. The NAP will hold its annual
convention on April 27.
</P>
<P>
NAP deputy leader Chalerm Yoobamrung speculated that Chavalit's
true intention was to tactfully remove party Secretary-General
Snoh Thienthong, in view of a growing undercurrent within the
party relating to preparations for the next general elections.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit's departure automatically terminated the tenure of the
party executives.
</P>
<P>
There were speculations that Chavalit had intended to seek a
fresh mandate for himself and the party executives to steer the
party through a new round of elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
