<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Makes Progress in Anti-Drug Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has made progress in its
national anti-drug campaign launched last December and drug
enforcement agencies have called for a more sustained effort in
the campaign against illicit drug trafficking and abuse.
</P>
<P>
Since December last year, the number of drug-related arrests
has jumped by 77 percent to 7,640 while 3,820 new drug cases have
been identified for further investigation, according to a report
recently released by the National Anti-Drug Committee on progress
of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the arrests and cases were recorded in four
targeted areas -- Hanoi, Ho Chi Minh City, the central province of
Nghe An and the northern border province of Lang Son.
</P>
<P>
During the first three months of the campaign, 541 drug-related
cases were prosecuted, with 857 persons put on trial by provincial
courts, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Since the introduction of the provisions on strengthening drug
control in the country in 1993, 128 criminals involved in drug
cases have been executed, including 60 in 1998 and 19 in the past
three months.
</P>
<P>
The report estimates that there are approximately 200,000 drug
addicts in Vietnam, with the majority under 25 years old.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's drug enforcement officers said drug abuse has never
before been so rampant among the country's student population.
</P>
<P>
Drug usage has even been discovered among officers of state
administrative agencies. One survey conducted in Vietnam's
transport and communications sector showed that the number of drug
users in the sector was as high as 7,000.
</P>
<P>
Officials have been also worried over the recent trend in
replanting opium plants in remote and isolated areas in 10
northern provinces, especially Lai Chau and Son La.
</P>
<P>
The report also noted that Vietnam is a major transshipment
thoroughfare for narcotics produced in the notorious "Golden
Triangle" opium-growing region bordering Myanmar, Laos and
Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
