<HEADLINE> Italy Hopes for Equal Merger With Deutsche Telekom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government hopes that
the proposed merger between Telecom Italia and Deutsche Telekom
will be on an equal basis, Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema said
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his weekly press briefing, D'Alema stressed that
before the merger can be taken into full consideration the method
and timetable for the privatization of Deutsche Telekom must be
made clear.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot accept that privatized Telecom Italia be merged with
a company which has the German state as its controlling
stockholder," D'Alema added.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the Italian government confirmed that Italy's
biggest telecommunication company Telecom Italia has a tentative
plan to merge with its German counterpart Deutsche Telekom to form
the world's second largest telecommunication group, following
Japan's NTT.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, Italian Finance Minister Vicenzo Visco said that
merger between the two telecom companies would have to be on a 50-
50 basis and the management of the new group should be absolutely
fair.
</P>
<P>
The German government, with 74 percent stake in hand, is
Deutsche Telekom's biggest shareholder while the Italian
government holds only 3.4 percent stake in privatized Telecom
Italia, so the Italian government urged the German government to
privatize Deutsche Telekom before the implementation of the
merger plan.
</P>
<P>
The proposed marriage, if realized, would create a 215-billion-
U.S. dollar telecommunication giant surpassing the hitherto
biggest Exxon-Mobil merger case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
