<HEADLINE> Mexico, US, Canada to Address Millennium Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from financial
sectors of Mexico, the United States and Canada will meet on April
29 in Washington to examine measures against the millennium bug, a
computer failure in interpreting time that could cause information
chaos.
</P>
<P>
Participants will discuss the issuing of more currencies to
meet the possible excessive demand of withdrawing by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
A top official in charge of computer systems of the Bank of
Mexico said Mexico's central bank will have a stock of some 10
billion U.S. dollars in case of a contingency caused by the demand.
</P>
<P>
The amount is equal to nearly half of daily electronic payments
of the bank, estimated at some 24 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
He assured that precautions have been taken to prevent the
possible repercussion on Mexico's projected inflation rate,
estimated by the government in 1999 at around 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The monetary basis will not be affected", he said.
</P>
<P>
Mexico will need about 350 million dollars to deal with the
millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
The central banks of the U.S. and Canada also announced to
issue more currencies to face an excess of demand at the end of
1999 in fear of the possible chaos caused by the millennium bug.
</P>
