<HEADLINE> Uruguay Limits Stopovers to U.K. Malvinas-Bound Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Uruguay decided on Monday to
impose a limit on the number of stopovers by British military
planes on its territory as it suspects they carry passengers "
surreptitiously" to the Malvinas (Falkland) Islands.
</P>
<P>
The decision, sent to London on Friday, obliged the British
government to keep the frequency to one or two military flights
per month.
</P>
<P>
Uruguayan Foreign Minister Didier Opertti has reportedly
informed his Argentine counterpart Guido di Tella and President
Carlos Manenm of the decision.
</P>
<P>
After Chile banned the landing of Malvinas-bound British war
planes due to General Augsto Pinochet's detention in London, the
British government requested Uruguay's assistance at the end of
last year.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay agreed that it would permit stopovers of passenger
planes in Montevideo provided they land somewhere in Argentina
first before heading for the Malvinas.
</P>
<P>
A British request for stopovers in Brazil has been rejected.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay, Brazil and Paraguay are Argentina's partners in the
Southern Common Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
Argentina is seeking to re-open commercial flights to the
Malvinas. However, Britain still prohibits Argentine planes from
landing on the disputed islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
