<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of the Macao SAR Basic Law (41) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 41 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
Will the public functionaries who have stayed on from the
previous Government continue to enjoy the same benefits and
treatment as before?
</P>
<P>
It is provided in Article 98 of the Basic Law that the public
functionaries who will continue their services after the
establishment of the MSAR will retain their salaries, allowances
and benefits no less favorable than before. They will also retain
their seniority.
</P>
<P>
It is clear from this provision that those public functionaries
who will continue their services will receive more pay and better
treatment than before.
</P>
<P>
Also, Article 98 of the Basic Law provides that the Government
of the MSAR shall pay to the public functionaries who are entitled
to them under the laws previously in force in Macao, remain in
employment when the MSAR is established, and retire afterwards, or
to their dependents, pensions and allowances due to them on terms
no less favorable than before, irrespective of their nationality
or place of residence.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Government and the public functionaries
themselves shall each pay a sum of money to the Fund of Pension of
Macao each month as a guarantee for the pension of the public
functionaries who are entitled to a pension according to law and
who will get it after their retirement.
</P>
<P>
Both the Government and the public functionaries themselves
shall pay their contribution to the Pension Fund at a certain
percentage.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the portion of the money in the Fund to be used to pay
the pension of the public functionaries who will retire after the
return of Macao shall be handed over to the MSAR.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alataw-Urumqi Train Route Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
URUMQI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A double-decker tourist train from
Alataw Pass in northwestern Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region
arrived here Monday morning after a 10-hour journey, marking the
opening of this new route.
</P>
<P>
Alataw Pass, 90 kilometers long and 20 kilometers wide, is a
passage linking China with central and western Asia, and is well-
known as a "wind funnel" due to its harsh weather.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, the State Council, China's highest government body,
approved Alataw Pass as an open port, and this new Eurasia Bridge
from the port city of Liangyungang in East China to Rotterdam in
the Netherlands is now fully linked.
</P>
<P>
Over the past eight years, the port has handled 8 million tons
of import and export goods and has turned over 1.5 billion yuan in
taxes to the State.
</P>
<P>
More than 190 domestic enterprises have invested in the port
and over 300 domestic and overseas-funded enterprises are doing
foreign trade business in Alataw Pass, which has been developed
into a 7-sq-km new town with sound infrastructure facilities.
</P>
<P>
The opening of this route will be significant for promoting
the local tourism industry and the economic development of western
China and opening it up to the outside world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
