<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Drops in First Quarter (Update) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- In the first quarter, China's
actual use of foreign investment slid down 14.6 percent from the
same period last year to 7.34 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the contractual foreign investment stood at 8.72 billion US
dollars, basically the same as the corresponding period in 1998,
said Ye Zhen, spokesman with the National Bureau of Statistics, at
today's press conference.
</P>
<P>
Exports witnessed a drop in the quarter as a result of the
impact of Asian financial crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics of the General Administration of
Customs, import and export climbed 0.3 percent to 70.26 billion US
dollars in the first quarter, of the total, export declined 7.9
percent to 37.27 billion US dollars, up 0.7 percentage points over
the fourth quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports rose 11.6 percent to 32.99 billion US dollars, up 8.9
percentage points over the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
The falling exports to Southeast Asian nations bottomed out in
the quarter and rose 1.8 percent while the growth of exports to
Europe and the United States witnessed a drop.
</P>
<P>
Of which, exports to the United States grew 8.4 percent, down
14.3 percentage points in terms of growth grate from the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports to European Union countries slid 2 percent as against
the 30.4 percent growth in the same period last year. Meanwhile,
the growth rate of exports to Africa, Oceania and Latin America
also slowed down distinctively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
