<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Allows Collectives to Contract Small Oil Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Small oil fields in the Tarim
Basin in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region are
now allowed to be contracted by collectives on a trial basis.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of the efforts of the Tarim Oil Exploration
and Development Headquarters to implement the State Council's
reform policies aiming to push the oil industry, which was once
under the influence of the planned economy and state monopoly, to
a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Since last March Ma Wenlong, a staff member of the Tarim oil
exploration area, has already piloted a project contracting a
small remote oil field together with 37 other colleagues.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that he was granted rights for the employment of
workers, purchase of materials, the use of funds and distribution
of income.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, our initiative can be brought into full play and better
economic results can be achieved," he said.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the contracts, Ma and his team will turn
over 12,000 tons of crude oil to the Headquarters a year. The
sales income of surplus oil is divided between Ma's team and the
headquarters in a ratio of 7:3.
</P>
<P>
Administrative expenses and the wages of the employees are paid
by the sales income owned by the team.
</P>
<P>
The output of Ma's oil field, the smallest in the Tarim Basin,
which has proven reserves of 860 million tons of oil and natural
gas, has increased to the present 80 tons per day compared with 30
tons a day before he took over.
</P>
<P>
The oil field originally turned out 170 tons of oil a day when
it first went into operation in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ma now employs 37 workers, only one-third of the original staff
members of the oil field. Production cost of oil per ton is 200
yuan, making up only 14 percent of the original cost.
</P>
<P>
"The contract and reform system is in the interests of both
individuals and enterprises," said Wu Xiaolin, an employee.
</P>
<P>
"We used to be paid the same no matter whether the output was
one ton or 10,000 tons. Now our income is directly linked to
production," said Wu.
</P>
<P>
Wu and his colleagues expressed the hope that the reform would
be further implemented.
</P>
<P>
According to an official in charge of the headquarters, all
three small oil fields that have been contracted by collectives
have achieved good economic performance.
</P>
<P>
However, he said frankly that the reform is still on a trial
basis. Some staff members still have doubts about the reform.
Stipulations and regulations are yet waiting to be worked out
properly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
