<HEADLINE> U.N. Urged to Play Role in Solving Yugoslavia Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov on Monday accused NATO of implementing a "scorched earth
tactic" in Yugoslavia and urged the United Nations to play an
active role in seeking a peaceful solution to the ongoing Balkan
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference here, Ivanov elaborated on
Russia's proposal for a peaceful settlement of the conflict in
Yugoslavia which has suffered from more than three weeks of
massive bombardment by NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
Among the preconditions for a peaceful solution, Ivanov said,
all forms of military operations including "violence and
oppression" should be halted in Yugoslavia and NATO should
withdraw its offensive troops from Yugoslavia's neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, Belgrade should pull extra troops and
police force out of its southern province of Kosovo, guarantee
safe returns of refugees of different races and religious beliefs,
and facilitate work of international humanitarian organizations in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also includes a resumption of political
negotiations between Yugoslav leaders and ethnic Albanian leaders
in Kosovo on an extensive autonomy in the southern Yugoslav
province and international assistance in economic reconstruction
in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said the implementation of the plan needs extensive
international help and the United Nations with rich experience in
peacekeeping should play a vital role in ending the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said he believed NATO is planning to launch ground
operations against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
According to Ivanov, NATO's ground operation plans include
partial occupation of Kosovo and subjecting it to NATO's military
control or dismembering Yugoslavia after occupying the entire
Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
NATO troops are carrying out a brutal "scorched earth tactic"
in Yugoslavia to pave the way for NATO's occupation of the country,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
