<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Neolithic Burial Ground Unearthed in Central-south China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A large burial ground dating
back to the middle period of the Neolithic Age some 7,000 years
ago was recently unearthed in Tujiatai in central-south China's
Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Covering an area of more than 30,000 square meters, the
Tujiatai Cultural Site is not only the largest primitive relic
ever found in the Dongting Lake area, one of the world's oldest
rice-growing areas, but also the most ancient archeological find
yet discovered in the southern reaches of the Yangtze River,
China's longest.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists have unearthed 16 graves over a 150-sq-m area
where they found three skeletal remains, two men and a woman.
</P>
<P>
These primitive people, 1.6-1.8 meters tall, were not much
different from their modern descendants, according to Zhang
Qinglong, head of the excavating team, which began the work in the
area last month.
</P>
<P>
One of the tombs is in the shape of a canoe 3.2 meters long and
0.6 meter wide. Zhang explained that the canoe must have been the
main means of transport by which the these people keep in touch
with the outer world, because Tujiatai was an islet in the lake
several thousands years ago.
</P>
<P>
A ceramic pot with grain decoration and in shape of a pair of
bulging breasts also was found in this tomb, which archeologists
say represents the worship of women's reproductive power in a
matrilineal society.
</P>
<P>
They believe this tomb is located in the center of the burial
ground because of its unique shape and artifacts, and also because
it is the only grave that is aligned from north to south.
</P>
<P>
A large amount of pottery has been unearthed at the site, the
oldest of which may date back some 8,000 to 9,000 years. The
archeologists said this find will be most valuable for studying
the primitive life-style, environment and plants of that time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
