<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Updated China's Economy Grows 8.3 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- China managed to maintain a fast
economic growth of 8.3 percent in the first quarter of this year,
despite the negative impact by the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
A double-digit expansion in fixed-asset investment and a steady
growth in consumer spending contributed to the bulk of the
nation's gross domestic product (GDP) that totaled 1.6784 trillion
yuan in the three months, spokesman Ye Zhen of the National Bureau
of Statistics told a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The farming sector witnessed a four percent growth during the
period, while the industrial sector chalked up an increase of 9.7
percent and the tertiary sector seven percent, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
"As the State's policy of increasing investment and stimulating
domestic demand keeps to take effect, the national economy has
maintained a favorable momentum," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fixed-asset investment expanded by 22.7 percent year-on-year in
the first quarter and the sales volume of consumer goods rose 7.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
Profitability of enterprises picked up markedly as a result.
The industrial sector recorded a net profit of 11.27 billion yuan,
six times more than the same period of last year, and the number
of loss makers fell in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that a deflationary trend has continued, with the
retail price index down 2.9 percent from the same period of last
year and the consumer price index falling by 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, both urban and rural residents saw their pockets
swelling faster than last year. The average income per capita of
urban residents rose eight percent in real terms and that of rural
residents rose 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
But Ye cautioned that a remarkable slide in exports has been
dragging down the nation's economic growth and should be dealt
with seriously.
</P>
<P>
During the first three months, China's total exports fell by 7.
9 percent to 37.27 billion U.S. dollars and imports rose by 11.6
percent to 32.99 billion U.S. dollars, leading to a drop in trade
surplus.
</P>
<P>
"Our estimation is that China's exports this year will be most
probably less than last year's, or match that at best," Ye said.
</P>
<P>
Capital inflow also slowed down as the actual use of foreign
funds dipped by 14.6 percent to 7.34 billion U.S. dollars,
indicating there was still huge pressure from the impact by the
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, contractual direct foreign investment stood at 8.72
billion U.S. dollars, about the same as in the first quarter of
last year, which suggested a possible turnaround in the trend of
capital inflow some time in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that the State's pro-active fiscal policy should be
further carried out to expand domestic demand, which is vital to
keeping a fast economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The government should also take effective measures to stimulate
private investment and consumer spending so as to offset the drop
in exports, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
He forecast an eight percent economic growth in the first half
of this year and regarded the central government's projection of
seven percent growth for the whole year as achievable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
