<HEADLINE> Georgia to Stay with CIS Security Pact If Conditions Met </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze said Monday that his country would stay with the
Collective Security Pact of the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS) if Georgia's conditions, proposals and requirements are met.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze told a press conference in the capital of Georgia,
Tbilisi, that rejecting earlier this month the renewal of the
treaty did not mean that Georgia had quit from it entirely,
according to Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
The president announced in a broadcast address on April 5 that
Georgia would give up its membership in the 1992 pact, which
expires this month, because participation in the treaty did not
bring any positive effects to the process of resolving the problem
of Abkhazia, a Georgian autonomous republic seeking independence
for a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that military cooperation between Georgia and
Russia needs improvement although the two countries have already
made progress in this area under bilateral commitment.
</P>
<P>
Georgia, which has Russian military presence, would continue to
work with Russia, adding that the scale and development of the
cooperation would depend on concrete conditions. 
</P>
