<HEADLINE> EDS-Details Added 7-Percent Target Attainable, SDPC Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The State Development Planning
Commission (SDPC), China's top economic policy maker, said today
that the country can expect a growth rate of eight percent for the
first half this year and that the government's projected seven
percent growth rate for the whole of 1999 is attainable.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, SDPC spokesman Zheng Xinli
said the economic recovery which began in the third quarter of
1998 has continued into the first quarter of this year, which
witnessed an 8.3 percent growth rate.
</P>
<P>
He attributed this encouraging development to the
implementation of government policies to increase investment in
infrastructure construction and stimulate domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the economy in the first three
months was characterized by the continued rapid growth of fixed-
asset investment and the improvement of investment structure.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the same period last year, investment in fixed
assets rose by 22.7 percent, while investment in agriculture,
transportation and post and telecommunications, and housing
sectors grew 122.1 percent, 46 percent and 35.5 percent,
respectively, the SDPC said.
</P>
<P>
The first quarter also saw a high growth rate and a remarkable
improvement in economic efficiency in the industrial sector, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to increased investment, industrial added value in the
first three months increased by 10.1 percent over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The highest growth rate was reported in the electronics sectors,
with the production of program-controlled switchboards, mobile
telecommunications equipment, personal computers, air conditioners
and color television sets all up by more than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
A particularly encouraging development is in the state-owned
industrial sector, which recorded a profit of 950 million yuan in
the first two months this year, compared with a loss of 5.46
billion yuan in the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The sales of manufactured products also recorded a steady
growth. The SDPC said sales of consumer products hit 760.4 billion
yuan in the first three months, a growth of 7.4 percent, or 10.6
percent in real terms when adjusted for the drop in consumer
prices.
</P>
<P>
The government's fiscal revenue increased by 26.1 percent in
the first quarter to stand at 232.4 billion yuan. Banks across the
country extended new loans totaling 143.7 billion yuan, an
increase of 52.3 billion yuan over the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The country's total foreign exchange reserves stood at 146.63
billion U.S. dollars by the end of March, an increase of 1.67
billion dollars over the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The SDPC said the major problem facing the Chinese economy now
is the severe export situation due to the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The drop in export's contribution to economic growth and in the
in-flow of foreign capital must be made up by further stimulating
the domestic market, the SDPC said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
