<HEADLINE> Myanmar-Bangladesh Border Trade Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has been able to carry out
direct cargo shipment to Bangladesh without the need to export to
that country via Singapore following the opening of one more
border trade point in western and coastal Rakhine state.
</P>
<P>
Sittway, the new border trade point on the Myanmar side, is the
second one opened last December in addition to the existing
Maungtaw which is also located in the same state.
</P>
<P>
Cargo has been able to be shipped directly from Sittway to
Bangladesh on an F.O.B. basis, thus facilitating trade activities
between the two countries bordering the Bay of Bengal.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Ministry of Commerce has asked companies in the
country conducting border trade to apply for the undertakings with
the requirement that a foreign currency account must be opened
with the state-run Myanmar Economic Bank in Sittway, according to
the latest issue of the local Myanmar Business News.
</P>
<P>
In the past, a majority of Myanmar's exports to Bangladesh had
to be shipped via Singapore, resulting in inactive trade relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Bangladesh initiated formal border trade in
September 1995 at the Maungtaw (Myanmar)- Teknaf (southeastern
Bangladesh) trade point. Their bilateral border trade stood at
5.6 million U.S. dollars in fiscal 1997-98 which ended in March,
the Business News said, adding that the trade volume for the
first nine months of 1998 was 2.3 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding, signed between the two
countries' major trade organizations in July last year in Dhaka,
envisages trade expansion and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Both Myanmar and Bangladesh are members of the BIMST-EC, a
sub-regional economic grouping formed in June 1997 by Bangladesh,
India, Myanmar, Sri Lanka and Thailand bordering the Bay of
Bengal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar has also opened six border trade points with
neighboring China in the northeast, four with Thailand in the
southeast and one with India in the northwest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
