<HEADLINE> Spaniard Puras Leads Catalunya Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Spanish driver Jesus Puras led the
Catalunya Rally by seven seconds on Monday as Citroen occupied the
top two places ahead of French driver Didier Auriol of Toyota.
</P>
<P>
Briton Colin McRae, winner of the last two championship rallies,
finished a distant 33rd place, almost seven and a half minutes off
the pace, because of mechanical problems in the fifth and sixth
stages.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, his Ford team said they would treat the rest of
the rally as a test session ahead of next month's all-asphalt
Corsican event.
</P>
<P>
Puras won four out of the day's seven stages after the opening
run was cancelled due to spectator safety concerns, teammate
Philippe Bugalski of France finished in second position.
</P>
<P>
The lighter two-wheel drive F2 cars hold a distinct advantage
over their four-wheel drive counterparts with their power-to-
weight ratio ideally suited to Catalunya's conditions.
</P>
<P>
The regulations allow Formula Two cars a minimum weight of 960
kilograms compared to the 1,230 kg minimum for four-wheel drive
competitors.
</P>
<P>
The Toyota pairing of Auriol and Spain's Carlos Sainz finished
in third and fourth position respectively, less than 20 seconds
behind leader Puras.
</P>
<P>
Auriol, winner of the event last year, broke two wheel rims on
the fifth stage but set the fastest time on the next test.
</P>
<P>
Reigning champion Tommi Makinen of Finland won the fourth stage
of the day and completed the leg in fifth spot, 34.3 seconds
adrift with Belgian Freddy Loix in sixth.
</P>
<P>
Skoda had German Armin Schwarz in eighth place.
</P>
<P>
The drivers face six stages on the longest leg of the rally on
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
