<HEADLINE> Philippines' Treasury Bill Rate Falls to 2-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' 91-day Treasury
bill (T-bill) rate fell to a 25-month low of 10.361 percent Monday
while the peso breached the 38 to a dollar level, Manila Bulletin
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the average 91-day T-bill dropped to a two-year
low of 10.361 percent Monday, or 0.611 percentage points lower
than the previous week's 10.972 percent.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper attributed the drop of the T-bill rate to the
reduction in the overnight lending and borrowing rates of the
central bank as well as the one percentage point cut in liquidity
reserves recently.
</P>
<P>
The central bank Monday sanctioned the sharpest cuts in its
overnight borrowing and lending rates so far this year. Its
borrowing and lending rates were lowered by 0.5 percentage points
to 10.875 percent and 12.875 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted monetary authorities as saying there was still
room for further rate cuts in the central bank's overnight lending
and borrowing rates.
</P>
<P>
As interest rates continued to drop, the exchange rate also
took the same direction with the peso appreciating by as much as 9
centavos Monday, closing at 37.95 pesos against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted sources as saying the monetary authorities
have bought 1.8 billion U.S. dollars since January, boosting the
gross international reserves in the process to 13.4 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
