<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Capital Goods Imports Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's capital goods imports
last year dropped by 37.68 percent to 5.79 billion U.S. dollars
from a year earlier as a result of sluggish investment, a
government report said.
</P>
<P>
Among the capital goods whose import drastically declined last
year were stone, vegetable oil and leather processing machines, a
report issued by the Industry and Trade Ministry Monday said.
</P>
<P>
The import of stone processing machines dropped by 79.67
percent to 22.54 million dollars, vegetable oil processing
machines 74.17 percent to 13.8 million dollars and leather
processing machines 63.09 percent to 4.46 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the import of pulp factory equipment was up 36.7
percent to 312.76 million dollars and cable manufacturing machines
12.74 percent to 17.93 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The import of electrical machines (generators and transformers)
was down 48.48 percent to 356.89 million dollars and factory
equipment 39.43 percent to 729.21 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Only the import of electricity power generators (turbines)
increased 70.36 percent to 126.22 million dollars, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Other capital goods whose import drastically declined were
passenger cars, electronic and telecommunications equipment and
agricultural machines and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia imported capital goods worth 9.28 billion dollars in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The Investment Coordinating Board said it last year licensed
152 domestic investment projects against 351 projects in 1997
while the number of foreign investment projects approved last year
dropped to 221 from 259 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The agency attributed the drop in the number of investment
projects to funding, marketing and raw material difficulties as a
result of the prolonged economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
