<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Sign Fisheries Accord With Seychelles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will sign an offshore
fisheries agreement with the Seychelles, enabling the Thai fleet
to catch fish off Africa next year, according to the Thai
Fisheries Department.
</P>
<P>
the Seychelles is a source of tuna for many countries including
France, Japan and Spain. The Thai fleet has never fished in the
western Indian Ocean because Thailand has not negotiated offshore
fishery rights.
</P>
<P>
Dhammarong Prakobboon, director-general of the department, was
quoted Tuesday by the Bangkok Post as saying the agreement has
many advantages. First, there is no need for Thai trawlers to
change their nationality to that of the host country as required
by some nations.
</P>
<P>
Second, the Seychelles does not have a law requiring Thai
fleets to hire local workers as the country has only 70,000
people. Third, the license fee is very reasonable compared with
the sums charged by Indonesia and Myanmar. Fourth, Thai ships can
catch fish for six months a year off the Seychelles, a longer
season than in some areas.
</P>
<P>
The Seychelles also has big tuna-processing factories that want
to buy large volumes of tuna, so Thai trawlers can supply tuna to
those factories before bringing any remaining fish to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The Seychelles' agriculture minister, Pronnie Jumeau, is
scheduled to visit Thailand in November to discuss the cooperation
agreement in detail.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, the world's largest canned-tuna exporter, imports
more than 13 billion baht (351 million U.S. dollars) worth of tuna
annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
