<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> University Heads Gather in HK on Global Higher Education Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Over 40 heads of prestigious
institutions of higher learning from Britain, Canada, Australia,
China's Mainland, Hong Kong and Taiwan met at a forum here Monday
to discuss strategies for higher education development in the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
The Vice-Chancellors and Presidents Forum on "Global Tertiary
Education Development," which opened at the Chinese University of
Hong Kong, is hosted by the Association of University Presidents
of China with an aim to promote international cooperation among
leading tertiary institutions.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the three-day forum, Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) stressed the importance of collaboration among
universities around the world.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that whilst the codification and transmission of
existing knowledge could be, though not satisfactorily, done
locally, the creation of new knowledge is wholly dependent on an
awareness of what is happening globally.
</P>
<P>
With the advent of information technology, "the need to have
some quality assurance mechanism not just at the national level
but the international level is more urgent than ever," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Also addressing the ceremony, Wei Yu, vice-minister of
Education of the People's Republic of China, briefed the audience
on China's strategy of developing the country by relying on
science and education and the reform of the education system in
China.
</P>
<P>
China's higher education system has developed not only through
its own efforts but also through its links with the development of
higher education in other countries and regions throughout the
world, Wei said.
</P>
<P>
"In the last 20 years of reform and opening up, China has
established international exchange and cooperation in education
with many countries, which brings about ever closer inter-
university relations," Wei said.
</P>
<P>
At the forum, Wei also delivered a special lecture on the
development of modern distance education and the construction of a
life-long learning system. Others who delivered special lectures
included professor Yang Chen-ning, the Nobel Laureate in Physics,
and Antony Leung, chairman of the education commission of the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Topics to be discussed at the forum include universities and
information technology, optimum size of university, management of
university, university research, science park, international
relationship, preparing students and graduate education and
lifelong education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
