<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cranes Find Heaven in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Local residents in the city of
Qiqihar in China's northernmost Heilongjiang Province have saved
101 cranes of different varieties over the past ten years, among
which 86 are red-crown cranes, and the other 15 are white cranes
and grey cranes.
</P>
<P>
A series of crane-protection measures taken by the local
government in the past few years, including publicity and severe
punishment for illegally hunting cranes, have instilled in the
residents' minds the importance of crane protection.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Deqi, a local farmer, found an injured crane while fishing.
He refused to sell it even at an attractive price, and instead he
took care of the bird for over ten days until it recovered before
returning it to the reserve.
</P>
<P>
A the volunteers' society for crane protection, set up in 1997
with more than 500 volunteers and some 300,000 yuan (36,000 U.S.
dollars) has also played an active role in crane protection. It
once saved two lost red-crown cranes which had strayed 1,000
kilometers away, and with the help of two farmers sent them back
to the nature reserve after a winter of caring for them.
</P>
<P>
Qiqihar is the main habitat for a number of rare birds, and 269
species, among which 35 are under state protection, are living in
the 210,000-hectare Zhalong State Nature Reserve in the
southeastern part of the city. Because of this, the city is also
called the Crane City for its large number and variety of cranes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
