<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prospects for Take-off Still Strong: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- China's potential to maintain a
high economic growth rate will continue for at least another two
or three decades, according to a leading economist here.
</P>
<P>
Lin Yifu, at the China Center for Economic Research at Beijing
University, held that the present economic slowdown by no means
indicates an exhaustion of China's long-term economic vitality.
</P>
<P>
Lin attributed the current flaccidity to the changing supply
and demand conditions, a tighter control over funds as part of the
ongoing banking reform, and the long-term effect of infrastructure
projects.
</P>
<P>
Around 1992, investment enthusiasm prevailed across China,
fanned by seemingly bottomless demand. However, as China started
to enter a buyer's market in 1995, good investment projects became
harder to find.
</P>
<P>
The country has also launched a campaign to straighten out the
financial sector in a bid to rule out mounting bad debts, low
efficiency and cyclical economic overheating.
</P>
<P>
Besides, infrastructure construction aimed at fueling the
growth of national economy cannot be expected to spark the markets
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
Lin explained his views in an article published in Tuesday's
China Daily, saying that a country's economic growth relies on
three factors: increase in various production elements, capital
and technological advances.
</P>
<P>
Countries and regions including Japan, the Republic of Korea,
Singapore and the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China
have sustained vibrant long-term economic growth through
introducing foreign technology and thereby expediting their own
industrial upgrading and economic transition.
</P>
<P>
When China embarked on the high economic growth track in the
late 1970s, the technology gap between China and developed
countries was much bigger than between Japan and the four small
Asian dragons when they started their economic take-off.
</P>
<P>
The process of bridging the technology gap will offer China
nearly 50 years of high economic growth, Lin said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the high proportion of China's rural population
leaves plenty of room for economic growth, and the country's high
capital accumulation rate will meet the enormous capital demand
while China is speeding up the pace of its economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
