<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outlook Improving, Salt Lake Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The head of fund-raising for
the Salt Lake City Olympics said that despite the loss of Johnson &AMP;
Johnson as a sponsor for the Winter Games, the outlook forsigning
sponsors is improving.
</P>
<P>
According to a report here, John Krimsky, head of Olympic
Properties of the United States, said today that Johnson &AMP; Johnson
made its decision in February during a meeting with Mitt Romney,
new president of SLOC, the Salt Lake City organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
"It's old news," Krimsky said. "They made their decision before
all the reports and reforms were made after the scandal. The
positive news is that we're talking to potential sponsors every
day. The outlook has improved."
</P>
<P>
No sponsors have signed since June, and talks stalled after the
Salt Lake City vote-buying scandal. Johnson &AMP; Johnson spokesman
John McKeegan said he did not blame the broken deal on the scandal
but said, "It was a backdrop to our discussions."
</P>
<P>
Romney doesn't share Krimsky's optimism. He announced budget
cuts last week because of a 350 million dollars shortfall he fears
taxpayers will have to pay. They must raise about 300 million
dollars to meet SLOC's 1.45 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
Krimsky says Romney's concerns are "premature until the scandal
gets behind us," adding he regarded last week's U.S. Senate
hearing as "our closure."
</P>
<P>
Krimsky intended to wrap up fund-raising in August but decided
in January to push that back a year.
</P>
<P>
"The sponsors that we talk to are assessing the environment in
which we find ourselves every single day," Krimsky said today. "
And when they have to invest millions of dollars and the
reputation of their products and service, they have to be very,
very careful."
</P>
<P>
Krimsky has complained that Salt Laker organizers have not
nailed down any in-state sponsors. "We cannot expect the rest of
the country to fund the Games unless we can state companies on the
scoreboard," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
