<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, April 20 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin Monday warned against
what he claims is an attempt by the U.S. to bring Yugoslavia under
its control.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton is attempting to make Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic concede and thereby make Yugoslavia
an American protectorate, said Yeltsin in a meeting with Russian
media chiefs.
</P>
<P>
Russia will not allow this to happen because the Balkans is a
strategic place, he said. (Yeltsin-Yugoslavia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The president of the U.N. Security Council,
Alain Dejammet of France, Monday said that the 15-member Council
welcomes the efforts by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on the
solution of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Council also agreed that the world body should "play a
significant role" on Kosovo, a Serbian province, Dejammet said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press here, Dejammet said, "Members
of the Security Council confirmed that they welcomed the efforts
of the Secretary-General to the solution of the crisis." (Annan-
Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie here Monday said
the bomb blast in a mosque in Jakarta is an attempt to stir up
political instability to sabotage the June 7 polls.
</P>
<P>
"This is an attempt to create an inter-religious and ethnic
conflict," the president was quoted by Investment Minister Hamzah
Haz at the state palace as saying.
</P>
<P>
An explosion, believed to be a bomb blast, took place on the
ground floor of Istiqlal Mosque at 3:00 p.m. Monday, wounding
several persons and destroying rooms in front of the Indonesian
Ulemas Council office. (Indonesia-Blast-Calm)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is
scheduled to pay a visit to Germany and Russia on Kosovo, a
Serbian province, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Annan will also appoint a special envoy to Kosovo, but the name
remains unknown at the moment, diplomatic sources said. (UN-Annan-
Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- China on Monday said that it favors a
political solution to the question of Kosovo, a Serbian province,
and opposes imposing any solution on the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia (FRY).
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by Qin Huasun, the Chinese permanent
representative to the United Nations, as he was speaking to
reporters here after a closed-door Security Council session on the
current situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We are deeply concerned over the deterioration of the
situation in the Balkan region caused by the continuing NATO
military strikes against the FRY," Qin said. "We are in favor of a
political solution of the question of Kosovo, the FRY." (China-
Kosovo) 
</P>
