<HEADLINE> Philippine Army to Resume Anti-Rebel Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Armed Forces of the
Philippines (AFP) are expected to resume normal counter-insurgency
action when the suspension of military operations (SOMO) against
rebels ends at midnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The SOMO is very specific up to April 19 and we will go back
to normal operation by then," AFP Chief of Staff Joselin B.
Nazareno told reporters on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada ordered the suspension of
military operations to pave the way for the release of Army
General Victor Obillo and Captain Eduardo Montealto. Both officers
were freed by the New People's Army (NPA) last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nazareno said Obillo and Montealto are still undergoing
debriefing at the AFP Intelligence Service.
</P>
<P>
Obillo is the highest ranking military officer captured by the
NPA in its guerrilla war with the government. Obillo and Montealto
had been held hostage for 59 days.
</P>
<P>
The debriefing will determine how extensive the two officers
had been influenced by their captors or if they had leaked any
sensitive information to the NPA, Nazareno said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
