<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Manufacturing Output Continues to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Economic slowdown and weak market
demand continued to drag down the output of the Philippines'
manufacturing in February 1999, the National Statistics Office
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The value of production of the manufacturing posted a
year-on-year drop of 8.1 percent in February 1999 while the volume
of production declined by 8.3 percent, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The value and volume of production of the country's
manufacturing sector contracted by 3.2 percent and 4.3 percent
respectively in January 1999 from a year earlier, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year decreases in February 1999 in value of
production were observed in seven out of 16 major sectors,
including petroleum products, basic metals, apparel, non-metallic
mineral products, transport equipment, food manufacturing and
paper and paper products.
</P>
<P>
The value of production in petroleum products posted the
biggest drop of 13.7 percent since October 1998 due to the
economic slowdown and also the low price of imported crude oil,
the office said.
</P>
<P>
Eight of the 16 sectors posted year-on-year decreases in the
volume of production during the period, led by food manufacturing
which dropped by 9.7 percent, the office said.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors which largely contributed to the decline of the
overall volume of production were apparel, basic metals, transport
equipment, non-metallic mineral, petroleum products, paper and
paper products and electrical machinery.
</P>
<P>
The situation was slightly improved when compared
month-on-month with January 1999, the office said.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing production had a near-zero month-on-month
contraction in February 1999 while sales turned in a double-digit
growth, it said.
</P>
<P>
On capacity utilization, the office said, manufacturing
establishments operating below 70-percent capacity were 41.8
percent in February 1999 compared with 39.4 percent a year ago,
the office said.
</P>
<P>
About 13.5 percent operated at full capacity in February 1999
compared with 17.8 percent a year ago, the office said.
</P>
<P>
Capacity utilization is defined as the ratio of output of a
plant to its maximum rated capacity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
