<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relics on Net, Websites to be Better Regulated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Computer networks should be used
to introduce Chinese culture to the world, while protecting
cultural relics, suggests a State Bureau of Cultural Relics
official.
</P>
<P>
"As a convenient and instant source of information, the
Internet can satisfy people's curiosity about ancient China and
help them understand Chinese culture," said Hou Junkun, director
of the bureau's Science and Education Division, quoted by today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Information about Chinese relics can be found at more than 60
websites. These sites were established by local museums and relics
bureaus primarily from Shannxi, Sichuan and Henan provinces and
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Hou stressed that establishments of these websites would not
have been so smooth without the efforts of devoted domestic
computer experts.
</P>
<P>
Foreign involvement, although not forbidden by the bureau, is
rare. To better regulate these websites, the bureau ordered them
placed under strict scrutiny last month.
</P>
<P>
Local museums and relics bureaus are required to obtain
official approval before introducing China's World Heritage sites,
places being excavated, the latest archaeological findings and
cultural relics under state protection on the Internet, according
to a bureau circular issued last month.
</P>
<P>
Computer and relics experts are preparing for a nationwide
information network of cultural relics, expected to be completed
this year. It will enhance research regarding relics and improve
the exchange of information.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
