<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Confident with Stability of Renminbi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A recent public opinion poll
shows that most Chinese residents are fully confident that the
Renminbi will remain stable amid the negative impact of the Asian
financial crisis, according to China Economic Times.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted in seven major Chinese cities, Beijing,
Shanghai, Guangzhou, Chongqing, Harbin, Dalian and Wuhan, and
indicates that about 76 percent of the polled people said "no"
when being questioned whether China would devalue its currency,
and 42 percent say that they are not worrying about it.
</P>
<P>
The survey, carried out by the Beijing-based Social Survey
Institute of China (SSIC), also shows that nearly two thirds
believe that China is capable of maintaining the stability of the
Renminbi, and another 18 percent say they believe in the Chinese
government's strong actions in keeping it stable.
</P>
<P>
Many people think that China has contributed a lot to
stabilizing the global economy in the past few years, and Hong
Kong's economy is strongly backed up by the central government's
promise that the yuan will not be devalued.
</P>
<P>
They also agree that devaluation will harm the interests of
foreign investors in China, at a cost of increasing China's debts
and threatening the stability of the Asian market.
</P>
<P>
China has a sound international payment system with revenues
exceeding expenditures and it has cut interest rates for the yuan
and raised export tax rebates. All these factors have provided a
solid foundation for stabilizing the Renminbi exchange rate,
according to financial specialists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
