<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> England to Bring 2,500 Children to 2006 World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and Britain's leading football knight Sir Bobby Charlton on Monday
launched England's Welcome to the World -- a project which will
bring more than 2,500 children from all corners of the globe to
England to take part in the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
It is the latest weapon that the organizers unveiled in the
battle to host the four-yearly extravegenza.
</P>
<P>
The project, which will cost four million pounds on bringing
children from all 203 FIFA affiliated members to spend two weeks
in England, is the main feature of England's theme for its bid --
Putting Young People First.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said that the children will have the chance to
attend World Cup matches, live with local families as part of a
cultural exchange, attend coaching sessions and generally enjoy
the World Cup experience.
</P>
<P>
All their travel and other expenses will be paid for out of the
profits of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
Alec McGivan, the director of England's bid, told a news
conference: "In what will be the world's biggest ever sports-
related cultural exchange, 12 young people from each of FIFA's 203
affiliated members will be invited to come to England for the
World Cup."
</P>
<P>
"We believe England's Welcome to the World to be the biggest
sport-related cultural exchange programme ever undertaken. It is
part of our vision to make the 2006 World Cup more than a sporting
festival. We will make it a great festival of international
friendship; about all a great festival of youth. We know the rest
of the footballing world will share our enthusiasm and our passion
for this idea," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair, speaking at No. 10 Downing Street
today, said: "Everyone is excited about the possibility of having
the World Cup in England, but we also want to create a football
legacy that will run beyond 2006.
</P>
<P>
"I know that young people are the future of this great sport. I
believe that England's commitment to put young people first will
make the 2006 World Cup in England a truly unique experience."
</P>
<P>
Sir Bobby Charlton said: "If our bid is successful, then it is
our hope that the impact of the tournament will reach far beyond
the 32 qualifying nations and far beyond 2006, It will mean that
every footballing nation in the world will share the experience of
England 2006."
</P>
<P>
The soccer legend denied suggestions that the offer was an
improper use of funds.
</P>
<P>
"If you want to be cynical, then people will say it's a kind of
bribe," said the 1966 World Cup winner.
</P>
<P>
"But it's not. We will make a good profit out of the World Cup
if we are successful and we should put some of it aside to give
back to the rest of the world," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sports Minister Tony Banks said that the minor crowd
trouble after Manchester United defeated Arsenal 2-1 in an epic F.
A. Cup semifinal replay last week would not have a negative impact
on England's bid.
</P>
<P>
Although Manchester United and Arsenal fans were seen to be
involved in scuffles on the pitch at Villa Park, Banks said: "
There was no trouble as far as I could see but a joyous fiesta of
football supporters who went on the pitch to cheer their heroes.
There might have been a minor fracas but it was not harmful to our
bid." 
</P>
</TEXT>
