<HEADLINE> Doherty Moves into Second Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Ireland's Ken Doherty advanced
into the second round of the World Snooker Championships in
Sheffield on Monday with a 10-3 victory over England's Steve James.
</P>
<P>
Doherty, 8-1 ahead overnight, saw James taking the first two
frames of the second session before he produced a century break
then potted a long black to secure victory.
</P>
<P>
Doherty, last year's runner-up, was left to reflect on a missed
opportunity to compile a maximum 147 -- worth 167,000 pounds (269,
600 U.S. dollars). His chance came in the penultimate frame when
his positioning let him down after sinking 13 reds and 13 blacks.
</P>
<P>
"It was a great opportunity because the balls were so nice," he
admitted. "I just got a bit straight on the black."
</P>
<P>
Doherty now faces Nigel Bond of England in the second round.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Alain Robidoux became the second seeded player
eliminated when he lost 10-6 against England's Nick Walker.
</P>
<P>
James Wattana of Thailand edged to a 5-4 overnight lead in his
first round, best-of-19 frames, clash with Hong Kong prospect
Marco Fu.
</P>
<P>
Fu, ranked 377th in the world, was making his championship
debut. 
</P>
