<HEADLINE> Berger Becomes New Coach of Frankfurt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Joerg Berger returned to coach the
struggling Eintracht Frankfurt Monday with the daunting task of
saving the club from relegation for the second time after 1989.
</P>
<P>
Berger, who took the helm of Frankfurt club from January 1989
through April 1991, succeeded Reinhold Fanz, who was fired the
previous day after only four months during which Frankfurt won
just one of nine games.
</P>
<P>
"I have come here to achieve the impossible in the last seven
games. I would not have taken the job if I didn't believe I could
do it. I am convinced it is possible, there are still 21 points on
offer," said the 54-year-old Berger.
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt are ranked 17th with 23 points, four shy of safe 15th
place currently occupied by SC Freiburg. Berger's contract runs
until June 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Fanz had replaced Horst Ehrmanntraut, who was fired December 8,
on January 2, but was under fire from club president Rolf Heller
from the first day. He was the seventh Bundesliga trainer forced
to leave early and the 245th in the league's 36-year history.
</P>
