<HEADLINE> Floods in Yangtze River Still Possible This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Big floods are still possible in
the Yangtze River valley this summer, especially in the middle and
upper reaches.
</P>
<P>
The warning came from Li Antian, director of the Yangtze River
Water Resources Committee (YRWRC), who said there is a high
probability that the upper river valley will experience bigger
floods than last year.
</P>
<P>
There has been little rainfall in the Yangtze River valley
since last winter and many experts predict that when it comes it
will be concentrated during the flood season this year, according
to experts at a recent meeting on flood control.
</P>
<P>
Jin Xingping, deputy chief engineer of the hydrology bureau
under the YRWRC, predicted that the highest water level of the
mainstream and tributary of the Yangtze, the longest river in
China, will be higher this year than that in the previous years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the possible increase in the number of typhoons in
the lower reaches will add to the possibility of big floods this
year.
</P>
<P>
Nie Rongfang, senior engineer with the Hunan Provincial Water
Resources Department, has called that regions in the valley should
be fully prepared for the possible disaster.
</P>
<P>
Local governments along the river have been asked to complete
anti-flood projects as quickly as possible.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Alerted to Protect Forests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The world's forests are
exploited far beyond their ability to reproduce, said the World
Commission on Forest and Sustainable Development, a
non-governmental organization on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 75 percent of West Africa's tropical forests have been
lost since 1950 while Thailand lost a third of its forests in just
10 years in the 1980s, said the group in a report.
</P>
<P>
Forests face an even shakier future with the global population
expected to grow 50 percent in the next half century, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
The Commission co-chaired by Former Swedish Prime Minister ola
Ullsten calls for a set of global, national and local-level
arrangements to involve people in all decisions concerning their
forests.
</P>
<P>
The report challenges a handful of countries with some 85
percent of the world's forests to exercise leadership in
protecting the forest environment.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi-based U.N. Environment Program said it is important
that the report offers a way out of the forest crisis the world is
facing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Refugee: We Want to Live in Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- An ethnic Albanian refugee, who
just arrived two day ago in Kukes, north Albania, said Monday that
Kosovo refugees want to live in peace.
</P>
<P>
Sitting in a tent which his six-member family was sharing with
another family of four, 24-year-old Ali Geci said that he heard
two huge explosions in the night of March 24.
</P>
<P>
Windows and doors of his house were shaken open, he recalled.
</P>
<P>
He, along with his wife, father, mother, younger sister and
brother was forced to leave their home in Mitrovica, a town 40
kilometers to the Kosovo capital of Pristina, on April 15.
</P>
<P>
They traveled three days to reach Kukes after crossing the
border at the Morina post.
</P>
<P>
"During the first night after our arrival, I slept in the open
air to let kids stay in the car and it was raining and cold. But
the second night we were given a tent and it was much better." he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he has loss contact with his elder sister, who has
a one-year-old baby, on their way to Albania.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know where she is now, " said the young man, who is
now helping Italian humanitarian workers to do sanitation work in
the refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
"We don't like the fighting and war in Kosovo and we want to
live in peace. When all this calms down, we will return to our
home. But for the moment, we want to go to Germany to join my
elder brother, " he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked if he thinks the German embassy will give them visas
to go, Geci replied he is not sure whether the German ambassador
will issue visas for them or not.
</P>
<P>
He said that he supports Imbrahim Rugova, the moderate ethnic
Albanian leader in Kosovo, who stands for a peaceful solution to
the Kosovo issue through political negotiations with Serbs.
</P>
<P>
"We can wait one year, two years or three years and for people
it is no problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
"What we want is a Kosovo with no Serb police and military. And
as for the common Serb people, they are free to choose to stay in
Kosovo or leave," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA), which is seen by Yugoslavia
as a terrorist organization, could not succeed because they have
no sufficient food to eat and no camps to live, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Almost all ethnic Albanians in Kosovo wants the problem to be
solved through peaceful means," said the young Kosovo Albanian,
whose wife prepared two small cups of coffee for us when the talk
was going on.
</P>
<P>
The coffee was good but the life here was miserable.
</P>
<P>
"Food is no problem. Besides other food items, every child can
have one liter of milk and adult half a liter each day, " Geci
said satisfactorily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Stop Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Conference on Use of Children
as Soldiers in Africa opened here Monday, calling African states
concerned to take measures to prevent children from being
conscripted.
</P>
<P>
The conference was hosted by the Mozambican Ministry of Social
Action Co- ordination, the Mozambican News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will focus on such issues as the use of children as
soldiers and the reintegration of these children into society.
</P>
<P>
Some 150 people representing governments of different African
countries, non-governmental organizations and international
institutions participated in the meeting which will last for four
days.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there are at least 300,000 children under
18 years of age involved in armed conflicts around the world.
</P>
<P>
U.N. representative for child soldier affairs, Olara Otunnu,
said at the opening of the meeting that the governments of African
states should take up the responsibility for protecting children
in the armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
He deplored that the wars in the continent have made thousands
of children killed or orphaned.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu pointed out that the governments concerned should make
efforts to sensitize the whole society so that no more children
would be involved in the conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Only the youths over 18 years of age can be recruited, he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. representative also suggested the establishment of "a
global commune" to help the children soldiers to return to society
through entertainment programs on radio and television.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the world community to help those children in
Kosovo who have neither drinking water nor food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
