<DOCNO> XIE19990420.0351 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Economist Predicts Gentle Global Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES. April 19 (Xinhua) -- An American economist said
Monday that the global economy is experiencing "a gentle recovery"
from its worst crisis in 60 years, citing the ability of the
international financial markets to withstand the fallout from
Brazil's currency devaluation.
</P>
<P>
Bharat Nauriyal, chief economist at Nationwide Insurance, one
of the U.S. largest diversified insurance and financial services
organizations, also pointed to the 52 percent jump in oil prices
over the last two months as another indicator of recovery. The
turnaround in oil prices presages a likely reversal in commodity
prices and could bear implications for the global inflation cycle
in the coming year, said the economist in Nationwide's
Second-Quarter Global Economic Outlook.
</P>
<P>
Nauriyal attributed the ongoing recovery to short-term rate
cuts and money-supply growth -- two factors that are
policy-induced rather than driven by changes in fundamental
economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that some concerns about the lasting power of
this recovery are justifiable.
</P>
<P>
Despite the recent 50 basis point cut in interest rates by the
European Central Bank, Nauriyal said that he remains inconvinced
that the global economy is fully out of trouble. He cited the
future of China's currency, a U.S. equity market correction led by
a pull-back in consumer spending and a Y2K problem-induced global
downturn next year as the "prominent risks" in this outlook.
</P>
<P>
While there are risks ahead, Nauriyal said that things could be
better if China upholds its pledge to not devalue its currency and
the gradual turnaround in Asia will continue to reinforce itself.
He added that the expected rate cuts finally delivered last week
by the European Central Bank will stimulate growth in Europe and
the U.S. will continue to remain prosperous long enough for global
imbalances to gradually work themselves out.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the United States, Nauriyal said that while a
slowdown is still forecast, this projection remains unusually
divorced from reality. Consumer confidence has almost regained its
record levels as the dynamics of falling unemployment and the
absence of inflation continue to boost real household income.
</P>
<P>
Considering that fourth-quarter 1999 growth in the United
States is likely to be abnormally strong this year due to
Y2K-related inventory buildup, Nauriyal said that this calls for
an upward revision of the 1999 U.S. growth projection from 2.3
percent to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Asia spearheaded by corporate restructuring, Nauriyal said
that a gradual recovery continues. He said that nowhere in Asia is
the scale of restructuring more prominent and visible than in
Japan, anticipating that unemployment will exceed 5 percent by
year end. With consumer spending down and Japan experiencing its
fifth straight quarterly decline in gross domestic product,
Nauriyal said that he expects the government to attempt to reflate
the economy by printing more money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
