<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Head Stresses Pregnancy Safety in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Director-General of the World
Health Organization (WHO), Gro Brundtland, Monday urged the
African countries to pay more attention to pregnancy safety.
</P>
<P>
She said in Maputo, capital of Mozambique, that Africa should
not lose precious human resources any longer, pledging that her
organization will fulfill its commitment to pregnancy safety.
</P>
<P>
Brundtland, who arrived here Monday for a two-day visit to the
southern African country, made the call at a forum on the issue of
maternal death.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican News Agency quoted her as saying that African
women face the highest danger of death when pregnant or when
giving birth compared with other women in the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
In some African countries, the maternal death rates at one of
every 16 pregnant women while in Europe or North America, the rate
is only one of every 4,000, she noted.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that about 8,000 Mozambican women die as giving
birth every year.
</P>
<P>
Brundtland held talks with Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano in Maputo Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chissano pledged to maintain good cooperation between
Mozambique and the World Health Organization, saying that his
government will give priority to health when working out programs.
</P>
<P>
This is Brundtland's first African trip after she was elected
Director- General of WHO last May. She will also visit Zimbabwe
and Cote d'Ivoire after her tour in Mozambique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
