<HEADLINE> U.S. Apache Helicopters Fail to Turn up in Tirana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Apache helicopters Monday
once again failed to turn up in the Rinas air force base in
Tirana, capital of Albania.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. Air Force officer told reporters that the Apaches would
not arrive Monday for reasons he said he did not know.
</P>
<P>
NATO supreme commander Wesley Clark, during his short visit to
Albania last Saturday, said that the 24 Apache helicopters, which
have arrived in an Italian air base, would come "very shortly".
</P>
<P>
It was widely speculated that the U.S. helicopters would come
on Sunday or Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Air Force officer said that he had no information on
when the helicopters will come eventually.
</P>
<P>
The Rinas air base, which has been put at the disposal of the
NATO forces, was not as hectic as it was on Sunday when
helicopters involved in humanitarian tasks and U.S. C-17 transport
jumbos carrying arms and army vehicles kept landing and taking off
almost non-stop.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Vehicles carrying guided missiles and launching
assemblies, which were seen being loaded onto trucks and carried
away to an unknown destination from the Rinas air base on Sunday,
were roaming on roads near the airport.
</P>
<P>
The presence of U.S. soldiers was more visible to the public
from a day ago as more and more U.S. armed vehicles with
heavily-armed soldiers mounting on top of them rolled out of the
airport and run on roads mixed with civilian cars.
</P>
<P>
NATO, which has been bombing Yugoslavia in a bid to make
Yugoslav President bow to its conditions for settling the Kosovo
crisis, is sending 8,000 troops to carry out what is called the
humanitarian "Allied Harbor" operation and 2,000 U.S. armymen to
man and support the 24 Apache helicopters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
