<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon: Apaches Due in Albania Tuesday (Wrap-up) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon announced Monday
that 24 Apache attack helicopters will move from Italy to their
new base in Albania on Tuesday and they could be ready for attacks
on Serbian forces in a week.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon hopes that the low-flying aircraft would increase
NATO's ability to destroy Serb tanks and troops sweeping Kosovo,
but would also be vulnerable to heavy Serb anti-aircraft fire.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a briefing at the Pentagon, U.S. Air Force Brig.
Gen. Charles Wald said that heavy rains in recent days had caused
very muddy conditions at Tirana airport, where the helicopters
will be based, but the Army had put down aluminum mats for them.
</P>
<P>
In another development on Monday,U.S. President Bill Clinton
said he would ask U.S. Congress for emergency funds to pay for
NATO's Kosovo air campaign and for resolving the refugee crisis
resulting from the war.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a White House event, Clinton did not say how much
is being requested, but said he hopes Congress will approve it
"right away."
</P>
<P>
However, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said it would be
roughly six billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Congressional sources said they expected the request to include
5.45 billion U.S. dollars for the war and about 491 million U.S.
dollars for the refugee crisis.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the emergency spending would "ensure that we have
the resources to sustain the air campaign to ensure that we
achieve our goals while maintaining our high level of general
military readiness."
</P>
<P>
"The need for this funding is urgent, immediate, clearly in the
national interest," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"There are... lives hanging in the balance. And so I hope in a
spirit of genuine bipartisanship the Congress will move the
package right away."
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Clinton spoke with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin for 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that Clinton and Yeltsin had spoken since
the start of the airstrikes, and the conversation came after
Yeltsin named a special envoy for the crisis last week.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said that the two reviewed the agreement and
disagreement concerning the Kosovo crisis. The two sides continue
to disagree on NATO's bombing and the deployment of NATO troops in
Kosovo to implement a peace agreement, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United States is seeking NATO support for
cutting off seaborne shipments of oil into Yugoslavia to limit
President Slobodan Milosevic's ability to fight ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Refusing to give details on the U.S. plan, Lockhart said only
that NATO was considering "a variety of things" that could loosen
Milosevic's grip on power.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that these are ideas that are worth pursuing, and
that's what's being discussed," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
